# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bernard-germain-de-lacépède
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/1793] The French Republic introduced the French Revolutionary Calendar starting with the year **I**.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The book was effectively the first "field guide" for non-specialists.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick provides an accurate illustration of each species, from life if possible, or from skins.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The common and scientific name(s) are listed, citing the naming authorities.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The bird is described, with its distribution and behaviour, often with extensive quotations from printed sources or correspondents.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Those who provided skins or information are acknowledged.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The species are grouped into families such as "Of the Falcon", using the limited and conflicting scientific sources of the time.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The families of land birds are further grouped into birds of prey, omnivorous birds, insectivorous birds, and granivorous birds, while the families of water birds are simply listed, with related families side by side.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Each species entry begins on a new page; any spaces at the ends of entries are filled with tail-pieces, small, often humorous woodcuts of country life.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] *British Birds* remains in print, and has attracted the attention of authors such as Jenny Uglow.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Critics note Bewick's skill as a naturalist as well as an engraver.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The arrangement of the species was by alphabetical order in Gessner's *Historia animalium*, and by arbitrary criteria in most other early works.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The first modern ornithology, intended to describe all the then-known birds worldwide, was produced by Ray and Willughby and published in Latin as *Ornithologiae Libri Tres* (*Three Books of Ornithology*) in 1676, and in English, as *The Ornithology of Francis Willughby of Middleton*, in 1678.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Its innovative features were an effective classification system based on anatomical features, including the bird's beak, feet and overall size, and a dichotomous key, which helped readers to identify birds by guiding them to the page describing that group.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The authors also placed an asterisk against species of which they had no first-hand knowledge, and were therefore unable to verify.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The commercial success of the *Ornithology* is unknown, but it was historically significant, influencing writers including René Réaumur, Mathurin Jacques Brisson, Georges Cuvier and Carl Linnaeus in compiling their own works.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] George Edwards was a leading British naturalist and illustrator in the 17th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] He was the librarian to the Royal College of Physicians with access to their collection of 8,000 books, and he used these, together with stuffed and live animals, to produce illustrated publications.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] His four-volume *A Natural History of Uncommon Birds* (1743–1751) and its three supplements covered more than 600 natural history topics, and his publications enabled Linnaeus to name 350 bird species, including many type specimens.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] When he was researching published sources for his bird project, Bewick relied particularly on Edwards' book and the multi-volume *Histoire Naturelle* of the French naturalist Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Thomas Bewick was born at Cherryburn, a house in the parish of Mickley, Northumberland, and he was apprenticed at the age of 14 to Ralph Beilby, an engraver in Newcastle upon Tyne, and learnt how to engrave on wood and metal.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The business prospered, becoming Newcastle's leading engraving service with an enviable reputation for high-quality work and good service.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Now partners, Bielby and Bewick published their *History of Quadrupeds* in 1790, and its success encouraged them to consider producing a new book on British birds.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] In preparation for this major work, Bewick spent several years engraving the necessary wood blocks.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick became well known for his engravings, including the woodcuts for Oliver Goldsmith's *Traveller* and *The Deserted Village*, for Thomas Parnell's *Hermit*, and for William Somervile's *Chase*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Perhaps the best known of his prints is *The Chillingham Bull*, executed on an exceptionally large woodblock for Marmaduke Tunstall, a Yorkshire landowner.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick also produced and illustrated several editions of Aesop's Fables throughout his creative life.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] His success meant that Bewick had at least 30 pupils who worked for him and Beilby as apprentices, the first of whom was his younger brother John.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick died at his home on 8 November 1828.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] He was buried in Ovingham churchyard, beside his late wife Isabella, who had died two years earlier on 1 February 1826, and not far from his parents and his brother John.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The preface to *A History of British Birds* states that "while one of the editors [Bewick] of this work was engaged in preparing the cuts, which are faithfully drawn from Nature, and engraved upon wood, the compilation of the descriptions ..
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] What the preface does not say is the reason for this statement about the "editors", which was an angry stand-off between Bewick and Beilby.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Beilby's original intention was to have an introduction which merely thanked Bewick for his "assistance", and a title-page naming Beilby as the sole author.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick's friend (and his wife's godfather) Thomas Hornby heard of this, and informed Bewick.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] An informal trade panel met to judge the matter, and the preface as printed was the result; Beilby's name did not appear on the title-page.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Each species of bird is presented in a few pages (generally between two and four; occasionally, as with the mallard or "Common Wild Duck", a few more).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The first item is a woodcut print of the bird, always either perched or standing on the ground, even in the case of water birds – such as the smew – that (as winter visitors) do not nest in Britain, and consequently are rarely seen away from water there.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick then presents the name, with variations, and the Latin and French equivalents.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] For example, "The Musk Duck" is also named on the line below as "Cairo, Guinea, or Indian Duck", and the next line "(*Anas moschata*, Linn.—*Le Canard Musque*, Buff.)" provides the scholarly references to the giving of the Latin binomial by Linnaeus (Linn) and a French description by Buffon (Buff).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The text begins by stating the size of the bird.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick then describes the bird, typically in one paragraph, naming any notable features such as the colour of the eyes ("irides"), the bill, the legs, and plumage on each part of the body.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Next, the origin and distribution of the species are discussed, with notes or quotations from authorities such as John Ray, Gilbert White and Buffon.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick then mentions any other facts of interest about the bird; in the case of the musk duck, this concerns its "musky smell, which arises from the liquor secreted in the glands on the rump".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] If the bird hybridizes with other species, this is described, along with whether the hybrids are fertile ("productive").
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Finally, Bewick acknowledges anyone who had helped him.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The musk duck is stated to have been drawn from a "living specimen" which was however "excepting the head, entirely white", unlike the "general appearance" shown in the woodcut; the bird "was lent to this work by William Losh, Esq., of Point Pleasant, near Newcastle".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Losh, one of Bewick's many collaborators, was a wealthy partner in Losh, Wilson and Bell, manufacturers of chemicals and iron.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Many of the birds, especially the rarer species, were necessarily illustrated from skins rather than from life.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] For example, for the Sabine's snipe, "The author was favoured by N.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The grouping of species gave Bewick difficulty, as the scientific sources of the time did not agree on how to arrange the species in families, or on a sequence or grouping of those families.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick, for example, uses family groups like "Of the Falcon", in which he includes buzzards and sparrowhawks as well as what are now called falcons.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Each account is closed with a miniature woodcut known from its position in the text as a tail-piece.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] These small artworks depict aspects of country life, often with humorous subjects, but all with Bewick's eye for detail, style, and precision.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Some add to the illustration of the bird in question, as for example the heron, where the tail-piece shows one heron catching an eel, and another flying away.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The tail-piece for Sabine's snipe, a gamebird, shows a hunter firing, and a small bird falling to the ground.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] There is no exclusion of human life from the images: one tail-piece depicts a works complete with smoking chimney beside a river.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The first volume "containing the History and Description of Land Birds" begins with a preface, an introduction, and a list of technical terms illustrated with Bewick's woodcuts.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The birds are divided into granivorous (grain eating) and carnivorous groups, which are explained in some detail.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The speed, senses, flight, migration, pairing behaviour and feeding of birds are then discussed, with observations from Spallanzani and Gilbert White, whose *Natural History and Antiquities of Selborne* was published in 1789.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The second volume "containing the History and Description of Water Birds" begins with its own preface, and its own introduction.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick discusses the question of where many seabirds go to breed, revisits the subject of migration, and concludes with reflections on "an all-wise Providence" as shown in Nature.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The 'foreign birds' are not grouped but just listed directly as species, from Bearded Vulture to Mino.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Fifteen birds are included, with no description, and despite their placement in the table of contents, they appear at the front of the volume as an 'Appendix'.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick's *Birds* was an immediate best-seller.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] When *Land Birds* appeared, the whole print sold out by the middle of 1798; 1000 copies of the demy size (8+3⁄4 in × 5+5⁄8 in, 220 mm × 140 mm), 850 of the royal octavo (10 in × 6+1⁄4 in, 250 mm × 160 mm), and 24 of the grand imperial (22 in × 30 in, 560 mm × 760 mm).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The 1829 *Magazine of Natural History* commented that "Montagu's *Ornithological Dictionary* and Bewick's *Birds* .. have rendered [the] department of natural history popular throughout the land".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The Tate Gallery writes that Bewick's " best illustrations ... are in his natural history books.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Dissenting from the general tone of praise for Bewick, Jacob Kainen cites claims that "many of the best tailpieces in the *History of British birds* were drawn by Robert Johnson", and that "the greater number of those contained in the second volume were engraved by Clennell.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] To Bewick, nature was the source of joy, challenge and perpetual consolation.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Hilary Spurling, reviewing Uglow's biography of Bewick in *The Observer*, writes that when *Birds* appeared, people all over Britain "became his pupils".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Spurling cites Charles Kingsley's story of his father's hunting friends from the New Forest mocking him for buying "a book 'about dicky-birds", until, astonished, they saw the book and discovered "things they had known all their lives and never even noticed".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The *History* is repeatedly mentioned in Charlotte Brontë's 1847 novel *Jane Eyre*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] John Reed throws the *History of British Birds* at Jane when she is ten; Jane uses the book as a place to which to escape, away from the painful Reed household; and Jane also bases her artwork on Bewick's illustrations.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Jane and Mr Rochester use bird names for each other, including linnet, dove, skylark, eagle, and falcon.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Peter Hall's 1974 film *Akenfield* (from the 1969 book by Ronald Blythe) contains a scene where the grandfather as a young man is reaping a cornfield.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] He weeps when he accidentally crushes a bird's egg, an image derived from Bewick's tail-piece woodcut for the partridge.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The woodcut shows a reaper with a scythe, a dead bird and its nest of a dozen eggs on the ground under the scythe, which has just lifted.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] George Ewart Evans used the image on the title-page of his 1956 book about Blaxhall (near Charsfield, on which 'Akenfield' is probably partly based).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick's reputation as a wood engraver was at its height in the nineteenth century, with the critic John Ruskin writing that the way Bewick had engraved the feathers of his birds was "the most masterly thing ever done in woodcutting".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The advent of mechanical printing techniques from the 1860s led to something of a decline in his importance, but his fame, already nationwide across Britain for his *Birds*, grew during the nineteenth century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] In 1830, William Yarrell named Bewick's swan in his honour, and Bewick's son Robert engraved the bird for later editions of *British Birds*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Bewick had met the American naturalist and bird painter John James Audubon in 1827, and had given him a copy of his *Quadrupeds* for his children.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The American returned the compliment by naming a newly-discovered US bird species as Bewick's wren in honour of his friend.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The way in which Bewick had organised the text and illustrations in his *Birds* takes the form of, and sets a precedent for, modern field guides.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Indeed, the French naturalist François Holandre (1753–1830) assembled a field guide using Bewick's woodcuts as early as 1800.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] A selection of tail-pieces from the book, where they have no captions.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Volume 1 first appeared in 1797, and was reprinted several times in 1797, then again in 1798 and 1800.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Volume 2 first appeared in 1804 (price 11.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] The first imprint was "Newcastle : Printed by Sol.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Hodgson, for Beilby & Bewick; London: Sold by them, and G.C. and J.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] In 1821 a new edition appeared with supplements to both volumes and additional figures, with the imprint "Printed by Edward Walker, Pilgrim-Street, for T.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/a-history-of-british-birds] Charnley, Newcastle; and Longman and co., London, 1821." The book was reprinted in many subsequent versions with a 6th edition in 1826, another in 1832, an 8th edition in 1847, and a royal octavo 'Memorial Edition' in 1885.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] During the last third of his life, he worked together with his son, Gerald Handerson Thayer, on a book about protective coloration in nature, titled *Concealing-Coloration in the Animal Kingdom*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] First published by Macmillan in 1909, then reissued in 1918, it may have had an effect on military camouflage during World War I.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] However it was roundly mocked by Theodore Roosevelt and others for its assumption that all animal coloration is cryptic.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Thayer also influenced American art through his efforts as a teacher, training apprentices in his New Hampshire studio.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Thayer was born in Boston to William Henry Thayer and Ellen Handerson, members of the Thayer family.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] The son of a country doctor, he spent his childhood in rural New Hampshire, near Keene, at the foot of Mount Monadnock.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] In that rural setting, he became an amateur naturalist (in his own words, he was "bird crazy"), a hunter and a trapper.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Thayer closely studied Audubon's *Birds of America*, experimented with taxidermy, and made his first artworks: watercolor paintings of animals.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] At the age of fifteen he was sent to the Chauncy Hall School in Boston, where he met Henry D.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Morse, an amateur artist who painted animals.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] With guidance from Morse, Abbott developed and improved his painting skills, focusing on depictions of birds and other wildlife, and soon began painting animal portraits on commission.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] He also taught his sister, Ellen Thayer Fisher, techniques that he was learning.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] At age 18, he relocated to Brooklyn, New York, to study painting at the Brooklyn Art School and the National Academy of Design. studying under Lemuel Wilmarth.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] He met many emerging and progressive artists during this period in New York, including his future wife, Kate Bloede and his close friend, Daniel Chester French.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] He showed work at the newly formed Society of American Artists, and continued refining his skills as an animal and landscape painter.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] In 1875, after having married Kate Bloede, he moved to Paris, where he studied for four years at the École des Beaux-Arts, with Henri Lehmann and Jean-Léon Gérôme, and where the American artist George de Forest Brush became his closest friend.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Returning to New York, he established his own portrait studio (which he shared with Daniel Chester French), became active in the Society of American Painters, and began to take in apprentices.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Life became all but unbearable for Thayer and his wife during the early 1880s, when two of their small children died unexpectedly, one year apart.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Emotionally devastated, they spent the next several years relocating from place to place.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Although he was not yet secure financially, Thayer's growing reputation resulted in more portrait commissions than he could accept.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Among his sitters were George Washington Cable, Mark Twain, and Henry James.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] He also made numerous portraits of the three remaining Thayer children, Mary, Gerald, and Gladys, and used them as models for symbolic compositions such as *Angel* (1887) and *Virgin Enthroned* (1891).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] After her father died, Thayer's wife lapsed into an irreversible melancholia, which led to her confinement in an asylum, the decline of her health, and her eventual death on May 3, 1891, from a lung infection.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Soon after, Thayer married their long-time friend, Emmeline "Emma" Buckingham Beach, whose grandfather Moses Yale Beach owned *The New York Sun*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] He and his second wife spent their remaining years in rural New Hampshire, living simply and working productively.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] In 1901, they settled permanently in Dublin, New Hampshire, where Thayer had grown up.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] The Thayer family frequently entertained prominent guests there such as Ralph Waldo Emerson and Mark Twain.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Eccentric and opinionated, Thayer grew more so as he aged, and his family's manner of living reflected his strong beliefs: the Thayers typically slept outdoors year-round in order to enjoy the benefits of fresh air, and the three children were never enrolled in a school.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] The younger two, Gerald and Gladys, shared their father's enthusiasms, and became painters.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] In 1898, Thayer visited St Ives, Cornwall and, with an introductory letter from C.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Hart Merriam, the Chief of the US Biological Survey in Washington, D.C., applied to the lord of the Manor of St Ives and Treloyhan, Henry Arthur Mornington Wellesley, the 3rd Earl Cowley, for permission to collect specimens of birds from the cliffs at St Ives.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] During this latter part of his life, among Thayer's neighbors was George de Forest Brush, with whom (when they were not quarreling) he collaborated on camouflage.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] It is difficult to categorize Thayer simply as an artist.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] He was often described in first-person accounts as eccentric and mercurial, and there is a parallel contradictory mixture of academic tradition, spontaneity and improvisation in his artistic methods.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] For example, he is largely known as a painter of "ideal figures", in which he portrayed women as embodiments of virtue, adorned in flowing white tunics and equipped with feathered angel's wings.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] At the same time, he did this using methods that were surprisingly unorthodox, such as purposely mixing dirt into the paint, or (in one instance at least, according to Rockwell Kent) using a broom instead of a brush to lessen the sense of rigidity in a newly finished, still-wet painting.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Thayer was largely surrounded by women, be they his family, housekeepers, models or students.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Biographer Ross Anderson believed that in his mind "feminine virtue and aesthetic grandeur were inextricably linked"; Thayer felt that the press and even other artists contributed to the degradation of women by emphasizing their sexuality, rather than exalting their moral attributes.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Thayer's first use of the theme was the painting *Angel*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] The wings were nailed into a board, in front of which his daughter Mary stood.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] He survived with the help of his patrons, among them the industrialist Charles Lang Freer.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Some of his finest works are in the collections of the Freer Gallery of Art, Metropolitan Museum of Art, National Academy of Design, Smithsonian American Art Museum, and Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Thayer was resourceful in his teaching, which he saw as a useful, inseparable part of his own studio work.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Among his devoted apprentices were Rockwell Kent, Louis Agassiz Fuertes, Richard Meryman, Barry Faulkner (Thayer's cousin), Alexander and William James (the sons of Harvard philosopher William James), and Thayer's own son and daughter, Gerald and Gladys.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] 1917, in the collection of the Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution), Thayer reveals that his method was to work on a new painting for only three days.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] If he worked longer on it, he said, he would either accomplish nothing or would ruin it.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] So on the fourth day, he would instead take a break, getting as far from the work as possible, but meanwhile instruct each student to make an exact copy of that three-day painting.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Then, when he did return to his studio, he would (in his words) "pounce on a copy and give it a three-day shove again".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] As a result, he would end up with alternate versions of the same painting, in substantially different finished states.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Thayer is sometimes referred to as the "father of camouflage".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Beginning in 1892, he wrote about the function of countershading in nature, by which forms appear less round and less solid through inverted shading, by which he accounted for the white undersides of animals.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] This finding is still accepted widely, and is sometimes now called *Thayer's Law*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] However, he became obsessed with the idea that all animals are camouflaged, spoiling his case by arguing that conspicuous birds like peacocks and flamingoes were in fact cryptically colored.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] He was vigorously attacked for this in a long paper by Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Thayer first became involved in military camouflage in 1898, during the Spanish–American War, when he and his friend George de Forest Brush proposed the use of protective coloration on American ships, using countershading.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] The two artists did obtain a patent for their idea in 1902, titled "Process of Treating the Outsides of Ships, etc., for Making Them Less Visible", in which their method is described as having been modeled on the coloration of a seagull.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Thayer and Brush's experiments with camouflage continued into World War I, both collaboratively and separately.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Gradually, Thayer and Brush entrusted their camouflage work to the responsibility of their sons.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] *Concealing-Coloration in the Animal Kingdom* (1909), which had taken seven years to prepare, was credited to Thayer's son, Gerald.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] At about the same time, Thayer once again proposed ship camouflage to the U.S.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Navy (and was again unsuccessful), this time working not with Brush, but with Brush's son, Gerome (named in honor of his father's teacher).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] In 1915, during World War I, Thayer made proposals to the British War Office, trying unsuccessfully to persuade them to adopt a disruptively patterned battledress, in place of monochrome khaki, though he was too anxious to attend the meeting in person.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Meanwhile, Thayer and Gerome Brush's proposal for the use of countershading in ship camouflage was approved for use on American ships, and a handful of Thayer enthusiasts (among them Barry Faulkner) recruited hundreds of artists to join the American Camouflage Corps.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Despite rapid changes in the art world in the early 20th century, Thayer's reputation remained strong.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] He was an early member of the American Academy of Arts and Letters.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Yale University offered him an honorary degree in 1916, and the Carnegie Institute in Pittsburgh mounted an exhibition of his work in 1919 that included over fifty paintings.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Monadnock became a favorite subject, and when the area was threatened with development Thayer campaigned successfully for its preservation.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] By his own admission, Thayer often suffered from a condition that is now known as bipolar disorder.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] In his letters, he described it as "the Abbott pendulum", by which his emotions alternated between the two extremes of (in his words) "all-wellity" and "sick disgust".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] This condition apparently worsened as the controversy grew about his camouflage findings, most notably when they were denounced by former U.S.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] As he aged, he suffered increasingly from panic attacks (which he termed "fright-fits"), nervous exhaustion, and suicidal thoughts, so much so that he was no longer allowed to go out in his boat alone on Dublin Pond.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Thayer continued to paint, but was compelled to stop working for weeks at a time due to nervous exhaustion.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] In an effort to avert suicidal thoughts, he sought help at a sanatorium in Wellesley, Massachusetts.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] At age 71, Thayer, disabled by a series of strokes, died quietly at home on May 29, 1921.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] In October 2008, a documentary film about Thayer's life and work premiered at the Smithsonian American Art Museum.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Titled *Invisible: Abbott Thayer and the Art of Camouflage,* it featured a wide selection of his drawings and paintings, archival photographs, historic documents, and interviews with humorist P.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] (whose father was Thayer's student), camouflage scholar Roy R.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/abbott-handerson-thayer] Behrens, Smithsonian curator Richard Murray, Thayer's friends and relatives, and others.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] The book's general method is to present a wide range of examples from across the animal kingdom of each type of coloration, including marine invertebrates and fishes as well as terrestrial insects, amphibians, reptiles, birds and mammals.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] The examples are supported by many of Cott's own drawings, diagrams, and photographs.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] This essentially descriptive natural history treatment is supplemented with accounts of experiments by Cott and others.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] The book had few precedents, but to some extent follows (and criticises) Abbott Handerson Thayer's 1909 *Concealing-Coloration in the Animal Kingdom*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] The book is divided into three parts: concealment, advertisement, and disguise.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Part 1, concealment, covers the methods of camouflage, which are colour resemblance, countershading, disruptive coloration, and shadow elimination.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] The effectiveness of these, arguments for and against them, and experimental evidence, are described.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Part 2, advertisement, covers the methods of becoming conspicuous, especially for warning displays in aposematic animals.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Examples are chosen from mammals, insects, reptiles and marine animals, and empirical evidence from feeding experiments with toads is presented.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Part 3, disguise, covers methods of mimicry that provide camouflage, as when animals resemble leaves or twigs, and markings and displays that help to deflect attack or to deceive predators with deimatic displays.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Both Batesian mimicry and Müllerian mimicry are treated as adaptive resemblance, much like camouflage, while a chapter is devoted to the mimicry and behaviour of the cuckoo.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] The concluding chapter admits that the book's force is cumulative, consisting of many small steps of reasoning, and being a wartime book, compares animals to military camouflage.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Cott's textbook was at once well received, being admired both by zoologists and naturalists and among allied soldiers.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Many officers carried a copy of the book with them in the field.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Since the war it has formed the basis for experimental investigation of camouflage, while its breadth of coverage and accuracy have ensured that it remains frequently cited in scientific papers.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Cott's method is to provide a large number of examples, illustrated with his own drawings or photographs, showing animals from different groups including fish, reptiles, birds and insects, especially butterflies.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] The examples are chosen to illustrate specific adaptations.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Cott was well aware that he was publishing in wartime.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] There are, as Julian Huxley remarks in his 'Introduction', references throughout the book to the human analogues of animal camouflage and concealment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] The book addresses its subject under three main headings: concealment, advertisement, and disguise.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Cott sets out his view that we have to be re-taught how to see, mentioning Ruskin's "innocence of the eye".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] He argues that camouflage should, and in animals actually does, use four mechanisms: colour resemblance, obliterative shading (i.e. countershading, the graded shading which conceals self-shadowing of the lower body), disruptive coloration, and shadow elimination.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Cott gives many examples such as a table of 16 species of green tropical tree-snakes.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Caterpillars and pupae (as in Poulton's famous experiment) are coloured to match their environment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Mountain hares change colour in winter; many fish, cephalopods, frogs, and crustacea can change colour rapidly.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] , Cott explains countershading with diagrams, photographs of models and examples of real animals.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] He analyses the component effects of disruption, including "differential blending" and "maximum disruptive contrast".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Cott's figure 7 is a set of nine drawings, arranged as a 3x3 table.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] On the left is an animal's outline in grey tone against a differently coloured background.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] In the centre, the same animals are now disruptively patterned against the same plain backgrounds.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] On the right, the disruptively patterned animals are shown against realistic broken backgrounds containing vegetation or rocks.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Cott goes on to explain that the right-hand drawing shows the effect "of broken surroundings in further blending and confusing the picture", observing that this is the closest to what is seen in nature.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] His readers are invited to look first at the right-hand images to gain an idea of the power of "these optical devices" as camouflage, putting off the moment when the animal is actually recognised.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Animals such as frogs are patterned so that when they are at rest with legs tucked in, their outline is powerfully disrupted with markings that seem to flow across body and leg boundaries.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Cast shadows give away even well-camouflaged animals.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Many animals therefore take care to minimise shadow, by lying down, with flattened bodies, or with fringes.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Some hawkmoth caterpillars have false shadow patterns to suggest they are parts of other objects.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] **Concealment in defence, mainly as illustrated by birds**.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] , such as in incubation and rest (sleep) in birds.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] For instance nightjars are nocturnal, and rest, well camouflaged, on the ground during the day.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Cott describes the care that predators take when approaching prey, minimizing visible movement and scent, the use of cover for ambush, and "adaptive silence".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] **Objections and evidence bearing on the theory of concealing coloration**.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] In this chapter Cott discusses various objections to the adaptive (evolutionary) nature of camouflage, and provides evidence to dismiss them.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] **The effectiveness of concealing coloration**.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Cott describes simple experiments such as that fish that have changed colour to match a pale background survived better (64% to 42%) on such a background than fish which had not.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] He also quotes some anecdotal observations on wild animals with similar but not quantified results.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] **The appearance and behaviour of aposematic animals**.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] They are often "sluggish", not running from predators; gregarious; and diurnal, since warning displays only work if they can be seen "by potential enemies".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] , is illustrated in a drawing by Cott, with its tail raised over the body, stretched up on all four legs, mouth wide open, and frills out both sides of the head, making it a startling sight.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Some marine animals select aposematic materials as coverings, not only as camouflage.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] **The nature and function of warning coloration, as illustrated by the mammalia**.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Prey like porcupines have warning colours, make noise, and attack predators (even leopards).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] **The Protective Attributes Of Aposematic Animals In General**.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Evidence is given that conspicuous animals such as caterpillars really are distasteful.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Animals with actual poisons are discussed, and how these are secreted, used in bites and stings, or kept to make the animal bitter tasting.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] **The relation between warning colours and distasteful attributes**.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Various kinds of evidence are presented for aposematism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] **The effectiveness of protective attributes associated with warning colours**.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Experimental evidence is presented that insects with warning colours are rejected by predators.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] **Experimental evidence that vertebrate enemies learn by experience**.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Experiments by Cott show that toads learn to avoid eating stinging bees.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] **Evidence of selective feeding by vertebrate enemies in a state of nature**.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Evidence from wild birds and toads demonstrates preferences for particular prey.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] **Special resemblance to particular objects**.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Cott describes leaf-like fish, chameleons, and insects, and other mimetic forms of camouflage.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] ) 160 times as long as it was thick is called "a revelation in the art of aggressive resemblance".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] **Adaptive behaviour in relation to special cryptic resemblance**.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Animals keep still, sway in the wind, or play dead to assist their camouflage.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] , sitting on its nest mimicking a broken branch.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] with "until/ Great Birnamwood to the Dunsinane hill/ Shall come against him" to introduce his chapter on the use of materials as camouflage.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Animals from crabs to caterpillars are described.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] A selection of lures and deceptive markings are described.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] with its spined forelegs raised and large spiral eyespots on its spread wings forming an image "suggestive of a formidable foe".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] , the four-eye butterfly fish, which are "usually towards the tail end" and tending to direct attack away from the head.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] and other camouflaged hunters are described.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Cott follows Poulton in treating mimicry as basically the same as camouflage or "adaptive resemblance".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] The behaviour of "Esquimaux seal-hunters" and First World War Q-ships are mentioned.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] **Breeding parasitism and mimicry in cuckoos**.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Huxley wrote a foreword (labelled 'Introduction') which defends the Darwinian concept of adaptation, especially of colour (in animals) and within that frame of mimicry.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] With objections dismissed, Huxley remarks that "Dr.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Huxley concluded his introduction by describing *Adaptive Coloration* as "in many respects the last word on the subject", upholding the great tradition of "scientific natural history".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Reviewers had little to compare *Adaptive Coloration* with.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Hubbs notes that Cott is seeming concerned about the scarcity of experimental data for the survival value of camouflage, and accordingly relies on Sumner and Isely's "clear-cut results", but at once continues that Cott relies on "the general lore of natural history".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Hubbs also remarks on the "resurgence to Darwinian views", referring to the scepticism about the power of natural selection among both geneticists of the time and to the Lamarckist views of Trofim Lysenko.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Concealment of an animal's ordinarily telltale shadow is also stressed".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Hubbs's review ends "This book is the work of an artist, and it is a work of art.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Cott and many remarkable instances of it are considered in detail".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] The review ends by mentioning that while biologists (of the 1930s) usually "reject the influence of Natural Selection in evolution, the facts of adaptive coloration as given in Mr.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Cott's work are a strong argument in its favour, and must be given due weight.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Over 60 years after its publication, *Adaptive Coloration in Animals* remains a core reference on the subject.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/adaptive-coloration-in-animals] Camouflage researcher Roy Behrens cites and discusses *Adaptive Coloration* frequently in his writings.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The **Age of Enlightenment**, also known as the **Age of Reason** or simply **the Enlightenment**, was a period of intellectual and cultural flourishing in Europe and Western civilization, emerging in the late 17th century in Western Europe.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] It reached its peak in the 18th century as its ideas spread more widely across Europe and into the European colonies in the Americas and Oceania.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Characterized by an emphasis on reason, empirical evidence, and the scientific method, the Enlightenment promoted ideals of individual liberty, religious tolerance, progress, and natural rights.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Its thinkers advocated for constitutional government, the separation of church and state, and the application of rational principles to social and political reform.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment emerged from and built upon the Scientific Revolution of the 16th and 17th centuries, which had established new methods of empirical inquiry through the work of figures such as Galileo Galilei, Johannes Kepler, Francis Bacon, Pierre Gassendi, Christiaan Huygens, and Isaac Newton.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Philosophical foundations were laid by thinkers including René Descartes, Thomas Hobbes, Baruch Spinoza, and John Locke, whose ideas about reason, natural rights, and empirical knowledge became central to Enlightenment thought.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Others cite the publication of Newton's *Principia Mathematica* (1687) as the culmination of the Scientific Revolution and the beginning of the Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] European historians traditionally dated its beginning with the death of Louis XIV of France in 1715 and its end with the outbreak of the French Revolution in 1789.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Many historians now date the end of the Enlightenment as the start of the 19th century, with the latest proposed year being the death of Immanuel Kant in 1804.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The movement was characterized by the widespread circulation of ideas through new institutions: scientific academies, literary salons, coffeehouses, Masonic lodges, and an expanding print culture of books, journals, and pamphlets.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The ideas of the Enlightenment undermined the authority of the monarchy and religious officials and paved the way for the political revolutions of the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] A variety of 19th-century movements, including liberalism, socialism, and neoclassicism, trace their intellectual heritage to the Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] By contrast, other intellectual currents included arguments in favour of anti-Christianity, Deism and Atheism, accompanied by demands for secular states, bans on religious education, suppression of monasteries, the suppression of the Jesuits, and the expulsion of religious orders.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment also faced contemporary criticism, later termed the "Counter-Enlightenment" by Sir Isaiah Berlin, which defended traditional religious and political authorities against rationalist critique.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment was preceded by and closely associated with the Scientific Revolution.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Earlier philosophers whose work influenced the Enlightenment included Francis Bacon, Pierre Gassendi, René Descartes, Thomas Hobbes, Baruch Spinoza, John Locke, Pierre Bayle, and Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Some of the figures of the Enlightenment included Cesare Beccaria, George Berkeley, Denis Diderot, David Hume, Immanuel Kant, Lord Monboddo, Montesquieu, Jean-Jacques Rousseau, Adam Smith, Roger Williams, Hugo Grotius, and Voltaire.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] One of the most influential Enlightenment publications was the **Encyclopédie** (*Encyclopedia*).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Published between 1751 and 1772 in 35 volumes, it was compiled by Diderot, Jean le Rond d'Alembert, and a team of 150 others.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The *Encyclopédie* helped spread the ideas of the Enlightenment across Europe and beyond.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Bacon's empiricism and Descartes' rationalist philosophy laid the foundation for enlightenment thinking.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Descartes' attempt to construct the sciences on a secure metaphysical foundation was not as successful as his method of doubt applied to philosophy, which led to a dualistic doctrine of mind and matter.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] His skepticism was refined by Locke's *Essay Concerning Human Understanding* (1690) and Hume's writings in the 1740s.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Descartes' dualism was challenged by Spinoza's uncompromising assertion of the unity of matter in his *Tractatus* (1670) and *Ethics* (1677).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The moderate variety tended to be deistic whereas the radical tendency separated the basis of morality entirely from theology.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Both lines of thought were eventually opposed by a conservative Counter-Enlightenment which sought a return to faith.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In the mid-18th century, Paris became the center of philosophic and scientific activity challenging traditional doctrines and dogmas.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] After the Edict of Fontainebleau in 1685, the relationship between church and the absolutist government was very strong.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The early enlightenment emerged in protest to these circumstances, gaining ground under the support of Madame de Pompadour, the mistress of Louis XV.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Called the *Siècle des Lumières,* the philosophical movement of the Enlightenment had already started by the early 18th century, when Pierre Bayle launched the popular and scholarly Enlightenment critique of religion.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] As a skeptic Bayle only partially accepted the philosophy and principles of rationality.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] He did draw a strict boundary between morality and religion.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The political philosopher Montesquieu introduced the idea of a separation of powers in a government, a concept which was enthusiastically adopted by the authors of the United States Constitution.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] While the *philosophes* of the French Enlightenment were not revolutionaries and many were members of the nobility, their ideas played an important part in undermining the legitimacy of the Old Regime and shaping the French Revolution.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Hume became a major figure in the skeptical philosophical and empiricist traditions of philosophy.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Kant tried to reconcile rationalism and religious belief, individual freedom and political authority, as well as map out a view of the public sphere through private and public reason.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Kant's work continued to influence German intellectual life and European philosophy more broadly well into the 20th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Mary Wollstonecraft was one of England's earliest feminist philosophers.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] She argued for a society based on reason and that women as well as men should be treated as rational beings.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] She is best known for her 1792 work, *A Vindication of the Rights of Woman*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Science played an important role in Enlightenment discourse and thought.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Many Enlightenment writers and thinkers had backgrounds in the sciences and associated scientific advancement with the overthrow of religion and traditional authority in favour of the development of free speech and thought.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The experiments of Antoine Lavoisier were used to create the first modern chemical plants in Paris, and the experiments of the Montgolfier brothers enabled them to launch the first manned flight in a hot air balloon in 1783.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Broadly speaking, Enlightenment science greatly valued empiricism and rational thought and was embedded with the Enlightenment ideal of advancement and progress.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The study of science, under the heading of natural philosophy, was divided into physics and a conglomerate grouping of chemistry and natural history, which included anatomy, biology, geology, mineralogy, and zoology.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] As with most Enlightenment views, the benefits of science were not seen universally: Rousseau criticized the sciences for distancing man from nature and not operating to make people happier.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Science during the Enlightenment was dominated by scientific societies and academies, which had largely replaced universities as centres of scientific research and development.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Societies and academies were also the backbone of the maturation of the scientific profession.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Scientific academies and societies grew out of the Scientific Revolution as the creators of scientific knowledge, in contrast to the scholasticism of the university.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Some societies created or retained links to universities, but contemporary sources distinguished universities from scientific societies by claiming that the university's utility was in the transmission of knowledge while societies functioned to create knowledge.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] As the role of universities in institutionalized science began to diminish, learned societies became the cornerstone of organized science.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Official scientific societies were chartered by the state to provide technical expertise.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Most societies were granted permission to oversee their own publications, control the election of new members and the administration of the society.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In the 18th century, a very large number of official academies and societies were founded in Europe; by 1789 there were over 70 official scientific societies.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In reference to this growth, Bernard de Fontenelle coined the term "the Age of Academies" to describe the 18th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Another important development was the popularization of science among an increasingly literate population.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] *Philosophes* introduced the public to many scientific theories, most notably through the *Encyclopédie* and the popularization of Newtonianism by Voltaire and Émilie du Châtelet.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Some historians have marked the 18th century as a drab period in the history of science.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The century saw significant advancements in the practice of medicine, mathematics, and physics; the development of biological taxonomy; a new understanding of magnetism and electricity; and the maturation of chemistry as a discipline, which established the foundations of modern chemistry.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The influence of science began appearing more commonly in poetry and literature.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] While some societies were established with ties to universities or maintained existing ones contemporary sources often distinguished between the two, asserting that universities primarily served to transmit knowledge, whereas scientific societies were oriented toward the creation of new knowledge.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] James Thomson penned his "A Poem to the Memory of Sir Isaac Newton," which mourned the loss of Newton and praised his science and legacy.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Modern sociology largely originated from this movement, and Hume's philosophical concepts that directly influenced James Madison (and thus the U.S.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Constitution), and as popularised by Dugald Stewart was the basis of classical liberalism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In 1776, Adam Smith published *The Wealth of Nations,* often considered the first work on modern economics as it had an immediate impact on British economic policy that continues into the 21st century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] It was immediately preceded and influenced by Anne Robert Jacques Turgot's drafts of *Reflections on the Formation and Distribution of Wealth* (1766).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Smith acknowledged indebtedness and possibly was the original English translator.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Beccaria, a jurist, criminologist, philosopher, and politician and one of the great Enlightenment writers, became famous for his masterpiece *Dei delitti e delle pene* (Of Crimes and Punishments, 1764).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] His treatise, translated into 22 languages, condemned torture and the death penalty and was a founding work in the field of penology and the classical school of criminology by promoting criminal justice.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Francesco Mario Pagano wrote studies such as *Saggi politici* (Political Essays, 1783); and *Considerazioni sul processo criminale* (Considerations on the Criminal Trial, 1787), which established him as an international authority on criminal law.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment has long been seen as the foundation of modern Western political and intellectual culture.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment brought political modernization to the West, in terms of introducing democratic values and institutions and the creation of modern, liberal democracies.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] This thesis has been widely accepted by scholars and has been reinforced by the large-scale studies by Robert Darnton, Roy Porter, and, most recently, by Jonathan Israel.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Enlightenment thought was deeply influential in the political realm.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] European rulers such as Catherine II of Russia, Joseph II of Austria, and Frederick II of Prussia tried to apply Enlightenment thought on religious and political tolerance, which became known as enlightened absolutism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Constitution during its framing in 1787.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke, one of the most influential Enlightenment thinkers, based his governance philosophy on social contract theory, a subject that permeated Enlightenment political thought.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] English philosopher Thomas Hobbes ushered in this new debate with his work *Leviathan* in 1651.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Both Locke and Rousseau developed social contract theories in *Two Treatises of Government* and *Discourse on Inequality*, respectively.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] While quite different works, Locke, Hobbes, and Rousseau agreed that a social contract, in which the government's authority lies in the consent of the governed, is necessary for man to live in civil society.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke defines the state of nature as a condition in which humans are rational and follow natural law, in which all men are born equal and with the right to life, liberty, and property.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] However, when one citizen breaks the law of nature both the transgressor and the victim enter into a state of war, from which it is virtually impossible to break free.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Therefore, Locke said that individuals enter into civil society to protect their natural rights via an "unbiased judge" or common authority, such as courts.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In contrast, Rousseau's conception relies on the supposition that "civil man" is corrupted, while "natural man" has no want he cannot fulfill himself.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Natural man is only taken out of the state of nature when the inequality associated with private property is established.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Rousseau said that people join into civil society via the social contract to achieve unity while preserving individual freedom.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] This is embodied in the sovereignty of the general will, the moral and collective legislative body constituted by citizens.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke is known for his statement that individuals have a right to "Life, Liberty, and Property," and his belief that the natural right to property is derived from labor.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Declaration of Independence and the French National Constituent Assembly's Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Some *philosophes* argued that the establishment of a contractual basis of rights would lead to the market mechanism and capitalism, the scientific method, religious tolerance, and the organization of states into self-governing republics through democratic means.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In this view, the tendency of the *philosophes* in particular to apply rationality to every problem is considered the essential change.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Although much of Enlightenment political thought was dominated by social contract theorists, Hume and Ferguson criticized this camp.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Hume's essay *Of the Original Contract* argues that governments derived from consent are rarely seen and civil government is grounded in a ruler's habitual authority and force.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] It is precisely because of the ruler's authority over-and-against the subject that the subject tacitly consents, and Hume says that the subjects would "never imagine that their consent made him sovereign," rather the authority did so.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Similarly, Ferguson did not believe citizens built the state, rather polities grew out of social development.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In his 1767 *An Essay on the History of Civil Society,* Ferguson uses the four stages of progress, a theory that was popular in Scotland at the time, to explain how humans advance from a hunting and gathering society to a commercial and civil society without agreeing to a social contract.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Both Rousseau's and Locke's social contract theories rest on the presupposition of natural rights, which are not a result of law or custom but are things that all men have in pre-political societies and are therefore universal and inalienable.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The most famous natural right formulation comes from Locke's *Second Treatise,* when he introduces the state of nature.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] For Locke, the law of nature is grounded on mutual security or the idea that one cannot infringe on another's natural rights, as every man is equal and has the same inalienable rights.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] These natural rights include perfect equality and freedom, as well as the right to preserve life and property.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke argues against indentured servitude on the basis that enslaving oneself goes against the law of nature because a person cannot surrender their own rights: freedom is absolute, and no one can take it away.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke argues that one person cannot enslave another because it is morally reprehensible, although he introduces a caveat by saying that enslavement of a lawful captive in time of war would not go against one's natural rights.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The leaders of the Enlightenment were not especially democratic, as they more often look to absolute monarchs as the key to imposing reforms designed by the intellectuals.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In several nations, rulers welcomed leaders of the Enlightenment at court and asked them to help design laws and programs to reform the system, typically to build stronger states.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] These rulers are called "enlightened despots" by historians.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] They included Frederick the Great of Prussia, Catherine the Great of Russia, Leopold II of Tuscany and Joseph II of Austria.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Joseph was over-enthusiastic, announcing many reforms that had little support so that revolts broke out and his regime became a comedy of errors, and nearly all his programs were reversed.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Senior ministers Pombal in Portugal and Johann Friedrich Struensee in Denmark also governed according to Enlightenment ideals.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In Poland, the model constitution of 1791 expressed Enlightenment ideals, but was in effect for only one year before the nation was partitioned among its neighbors.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] More enduring were the cultural achievements, which created a nationalist spirit in Poland.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Frederick the Great, the king of Prussia from 1740 to 1786, saw himself as a leader of the Enlightenment and patronized philosophers and scientists at his court in Berlin.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Voltaire, who had been imprisoned and maltreated by the French government, was eager to accept Frederick's invitation to live at his palace.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment has been frequently linked to the American Revolution of 1776 and the French Revolution of 1789—both had some intellectual influence from Thomas Jefferson.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] A key aspect of this era was a profound shift from the absolute monarchies of Europe, which asserted the "divine right" to rule.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] John Locke rejected this view in his writings on the Two Treatises of Government (1689).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] He asserted that citizens were seen to possess natural rights, including life, liberty, and property.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Therefore governments exist to protect these rights through the "consent of the governed." The clash between these competing ethos often resulted in violent upheaval in differing ways.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In France, Ancien régime, with its rigid social hierarchy and absolute monarchical power, was systematically dismantled during the French Revolution.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] While the American Revolution focused more on breaking free from a government - represented by King George III and Parliament - that colonists felt did not adequately represent their interests.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Alexis de Tocqueville proposed the French Revolution as the inevitable result of the radical opposition created in the 18th century between the monarchy and the men of letters of the Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] These men of letters constituted a sort of "substitute aristocracy that was both all-powerful and without real power." This illusory power came from the rise of "public opinion," born when absolutist centralization removed the nobility and the bourgeoisie from the political sphere.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The "literary politics" that resulted promoted a discourse of equality and was hence in fundamental opposition to the monarchical regime.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Enlightenment era religious commentary was a response to the preceding century of religious conflict in Europe, especially the Thirty Years' War.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Theologians of the Enlightenment wanted to reform their faith to its generally non-confrontational roots and to limit the capacity for religious controversy to spill over into politics and warfare while still maintaining a true faith in God.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] For moderate Christians, this meant a return to simple Scripture.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke abandoned the corpus of theological commentary in favor of an "unprejudiced examination" of the Word of God alone.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] He determined the essence of Christianity to be a belief in Christ the redeemer and recommended avoiding more detailed debate.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In the *Jefferson Bible,* Thomas Jefferson went further and dropped any passages dealing with miracles, visitations of angels, and the resurrection of Jesus after his death, as he tried to extract the practical Christian moral code of the New Testament.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Enlightenment scholars sought to curtail the political power of organized religion and thereby prevent another age of intolerant religious war.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Spinoza determined to remove politics from contemporary and historical theology (e.g., disregarding Judaic law).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Moses Mendelssohn advised affording no political weight to any organized religion but instead recommended that each person follow what they found most convincing.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] They believed a good religion based in instinctive morals and a belief in God should not theoretically need force to maintain order in its believers, and both Mendelssohn and Spinoza judged religion on its moral fruits, not the logic of its theology.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Several novel ideas about religion developed with the Enlightenment, including deism and talk of atheism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] According to Thomas Paine, deism is the simple belief in God the Creator with no reference to the Bible or any other miraculous source.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Instead, the deist relies solely on personal reason to guide his creed, which was eminently agreeable to many thinkers of the time.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Atheism was much discussed, but there were few proponents.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Wilson and Reill note: "In fact, very few enlightened intellectuals, even when they were vocal critics of Christianity, were true atheists.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Rather, they were critics of orthodox belief, wedded rather to skepticism, deism, vitalism, or perhaps pantheism." Some followed Pierre Bayle and argued that atheists could indeed be moral men.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Many others like Voltaire held that without belief in a God who punishes evil, the moral order of society was undermined; that is, since atheists gave themselves to no supreme authority and no law and had no fear of eternal consequences, they were far more likely to disrupt society.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Bayle observed that, in his day, "prudent persons will always maintain an appearance of [religion]," and he believed that even atheists could hold concepts of honor and go beyond their own self-interest to create and interact in society.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke said that if there were no God and no divine law, the result would be moral anarchy: every individual "could have no law but his own will, no end but himself.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The "Radical Enlightenment" promoted the concept of separating church and state, an idea that is often credited to Locke.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] According to his principle of the social contract, Locke said that the government lacked authority in the realm of individual conscience, as this was something rational people could not cede to the government for it or others to control.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] For Locke, this created a natural right in the liberty of conscience, which he said must therefore remain protected from any government authority.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] These views on religious tolerance and the importance of individual conscience, along with the social contract, became particularly influential in the American colonies and the drafting of the United States Constitution.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In a letter to the Danbury Baptist Association in Connecticut, Thomas Jefferson calls for a "wall of separation between church and state" at the federal level.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] He previously had supported successful efforts to disestablish the Church of England in Virginia and authored the Virginia Statute for Religious Freedom.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Jefferson's political ideals were greatly influenced by the writings of Locke, Bacon, and Newton, whom he considered the three greatest men that ever lived.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Enlightenment took hold in most European countries and influenced nations globally, often with a specific local emphasis.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] For example, in France it became associated with anti-government and anti-Church radicalism, while in Germany it reached deep into the middle classes, where it expressed a spiritualistic and nationalistic tone without threatening governments or established churches.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In France, the government was hostile, and the *philosophes* fought against its censorship, sometimes being imprisoned or hounded into exile.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The British government, for the most part, ignored the Enlightenment's leaders in England and Scotland, although it did give Newton a knighthood and a very lucrative government office.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] A common theme among most countries which derived Enlightenment ideas from Europe was the intentional non-inclusion of Enlightenment philosophies pertaining to slavery.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In 1791, the Haitian Revolution, a slave rebellion by emancipated slaves against French colonial rule in the colony of Saint-Domingue, broke out.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The very existence of an English Enlightenment has been hotly debated by scholars.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The majority of textbooks on British history make little or no mention of an English Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Some surveys of the entire Enlightenment include England and others ignore it, although they do include coverage of such major intellectuals as Joseph Addison, Edward Gibbon, John Locke, Isaac Newton, Alexander Pope, Joshua Reynolds, and Jonathan Swift.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Freethinking, a term describing those who stood in opposition to the institution of the Church, and the literal belief in the Bible, can be said to have begun in England no later than 1713, when Anthony Collins wrote his "Discourse of Free-thinking," which gained substantial popularity.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] This essay attacked the clergy of all churches and was a plea for deism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Roy Porter argues that the reasons for this neglect were the assumptions that the movement was primarily French-inspired, that it was largely a-religious or anti-clerical, and that it stood in outspoken defiance to the established order.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Porter admits that after the 1720s England could claim thinkers to equal Diderot, Voltaire, or Rousseau.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, its leading intellectuals such as Gibbon, Edmund Burke and Samuel Johnson were all quite conservative and supportive of the standing order.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Porter says the reason was that Enlightenment had come early to England and had succeeded such that the culture had accepted political liberalism, philosophical empiricism, and religious toleration, positions which intellectuals on the continent had to fight against powerful odds.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Furthermore, England rejected the collectivism of the continent and emphasized the improvement of individuals as the main goal of enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] According to Derek Hirst, the 1640s and 1650s saw a revived economy characterised by growth in manufacturing, the elaboration of financial and credit instruments, and the commercialisation of communication.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The gentry found time for leisure activities, such as horse racing and bowling.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In the high culture important innovations included the development of a mass market for music, increased scientific research, and an expansion of publishing.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] All the trends were discussed in depth at the newly established coffee houses.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In the Scottish Enlightenment, the principles of sociability, equality, and utility were disseminated in schools and universities, many of which used sophisticated teaching methods which blended philosophy with daily life.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Scotland's major cities created an intellectual infrastructure of mutually supporting institutions such as schools, universities, reading societies, libraries, periodicals, museums, and Masonic lodges.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Several Americans, especially Benjamin Franklin and Thomas Jefferson, played a major role in bringing Enlightenment ideas to the New World and in influencing British and French thinkers.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Franklin was influential for his political activism and for his advances in physics.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Franklin also broadly encouraged the individual's rights and responsibilities to serve as an educated and informed citizen.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] He published yearly the widely popular, *Poor Richard's Almanack,* filled with witty quotes encouraging disciplined self-learning, such as "Early to bed, early to rise, makes a man healthy, wealthy and wise." The cultural exchange during the Enlightenment ran in both directions across the Atlantic.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Thinkers such as Paine, Locke, and Rousseau all take Native American cultural practices as examples of natural freedom.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Americans closely followed English and Scottish political ideas, as well as some French thinkers such as Montesquieu.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] As deists, they were influenced by ideas of John Toland and Matthew Tindal.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] There was a great emphasis upon liberty, republicanism, and religious tolerance.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] There was no respect for monarchy or inherited political power.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Deists reconciled science and religion by rejecting prophecies, miracles, and biblical theology.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Leading deists included Thomas Paine in *The Age of Reason* and Thomas Jefferson in his short *Jefferson Bible,* from which he removed all supernatural aspects.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Jewish Enlightenment, or *Haskalah* (Hebrew: הַשְׂכָּלָה, "education") was an intellectual movement among the Jews of Central and Eastern Europe, with a certain influence on those in Western Europe and the Muslim world.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] It arose as a defined ideological worldview during the 1770s, and its last stage ended around 1881, with the rise of Jewish nationalism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement advocated against Jewish reclusiveness, encouraged the adoption of prevalent attire over traditional dress, while also working to diminish the authority of traditional community institutions such as rabbinic courts and boards of elders.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During the Early Dutch Enlightenment (1640–1720), many books were translated from Latin, French or English to Dutch, often at the risk of their translators and publishers.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] By the 1720s, the Dutch Republic had also become a major center for printing and exporting banned books to France.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Implanted in Netherlandish culture, vernacular rationalism brought the Dutch to take advantage of the intellectual philosophy the enlightenment spread.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The most famous figure of the Dutch Enlightenment was Baruch Spinoza.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The French Enlightenment was influenced by England and in turn influenced other national enlightenments.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Prussia took the lead among the German states in sponsoring the political reforms that Enlightenment thinkers urged absolute rulers to adopt.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] There were important movements as well in the smaller states of Bavaria, Saxony, Hanover, and the Palatinate.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In each case, Enlightenment values became accepted and led to significant political and administrative reforms that laid the groundwork for the creation of modern states.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The princes of Saxony, for example, carried out an impressive series of fundamental fiscal, administrative, judicial, educational, cultural, and general economic reforms.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The reforms were aided by the country's strong urban structure and influential commercial groups and modernized pre-1789 Saxony along the lines of classic Enlightenment principles.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Before 1750, the German upper classes looked to France for intellectual, cultural, and architectural leadership, as French was the language of high society.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] By the mid-18th century, the *Aufklärung* (The Enlightenment) had transformed German high culture in music, philosophy, science, and literature.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Christian Wolff was the pioneer as a writer who expounded the Enlightenment to German readers and legitimized German as a philosophic language.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Johann Gottfried von Herder broke new ground in philosophy and poetry, as a leader of the Sturm und Drang movement of proto-Romanticism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Weimar Classicism (*Weimarer Klassik*) was a cultural and literary movement based in Weimar that sought to establish a new humanism by synthesizing Romantic, classical, and Enlightenment ideas.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement (from 1772 until 1805) involved Herder as well as polymath Johann Wolfgang von Goethe and Friedrich Schiller, a poet and historian.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The theatre principal Abel Seyler greatly influenced the development of German theatre and promoted serious German opera, new works and experimental productions, and the concept of a national theatre.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Herder argued that every group of people had its own particular identity, which was expressed in its language and culture.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] This legitimized the promotion of German language and culture and helped shape the development of German nationalism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Schiller's plays expressed the restless spirit of his generation, depicting the hero's struggle against social pressures and the force of destiny.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] German music, sponsored by the upper classes, came of age under composers Johann Sebastian Bach, Joseph Haydn, and Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In remote Königsberg, Kant tried to reconcile rationalism and religious belief, individual freedom, and political authority.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Kant's work contained basic tensions that would continue to shape German thought—and indeed all of European philosophy—well into the 20th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] German Enlightenment won the support of princes, aristocrats, and the middle classes, and it permanently reshaped the culture.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, there was a conservatism among the elites that warned against going too far.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In 1788, Prussia issued an "Edict on Religion" that forbade preaching any sermon that undermined popular belief in the Holy Trinity or the Bible.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The goal was to avoid theological disputes that might impinge on domestic tranquility.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Men who doubted the value of Enlightenment favoured the measure, but so too did many supporters.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] German universities had created a closed elite that could debate controversial issues among themselves, but spreading them to the public was seen as too risky.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] This intellectual elite was favoured by the state, but that might be reversed if the process of the Enlightenment proved politically or socially destabilizing.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During the 18th century, Austria was under Habsburg rule.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The reign of Maria Theresa, the first Habsburg monarch to be considered influenced by the Enlightenment in some areas, was marked by a mix of enlightenment and conservatism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Her son Joseph II's brief reign was marked by this conflict, with his ideology of Josephinism facing opposition.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Joseph II carried out numerous reforms in the spirit of the Enlightenment, which affected, for example, the school system, monasteries and the legal system.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Emperor Leopold II, who was an early opponent of capital punishment, had a brief and contentious rule that was mostly marked by relations with France.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Similarly, Emperor Francis II's rule was primarily marked by relations with France.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The ideas of the Enlightenment also appeared in literature and theater works.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Joseph von Sonnenfels was an important representative.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In music, Austrian musicians such as Joseph Haydn and Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart were associated with the Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Modern Greek Enlightenment (Greek: Διαφωτισμός, Diafotismós) was the Greek expression of the Enlightenment, characterized by an intellectual and philosophical movement within the Greek community.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] At this time, many Greeks were dispersed across the Ottoman Empire, with some residing on the Ionian Islands, in Venice, and other parts of Italy.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Hungarian Enlightenment emerged during the 18th century, while Hungary was part of the Habsburg Empire.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Hungarian Enlightenment is usually said to have begun in 1772 and was greatly influenced by French Enlightenment (through Vienna).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Romanian Enlightenment emerged during the 18th century across the three major historical regions inhabited by Romanians: Transylvania, Wallachia, and Moldavia.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] At that time, Transylvania was in the Habsburg Empire while Wallachia and Moldavia were vassals of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Transylvanian Enlightenment was represented by the Transylvanian School, a group of thinkers who promoted a cultural revival and rights for Romanians (who were marginalized by the Habsburgs).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Wallachian Enlightenment was represented by such figures as Dinicu Golescu (1777–1830), while the Moldavian Englightenment was headed by prince Dimitrie Cantemir (1673-1723).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Enlightenment arrived relatively late in Switzerland, spreading from England, the Netherlands, and France toward the end of the 17th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement initially took hold in Protestant regions, where it gradually replaced orthodox religious thinking.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The 1712 victory of the reformed cantons of Zurich and Bern over the five Catholic cantons of central Switzerland in the Second War of Villmergen marked both a Protestant triumph and a victory for Enlightenment ideas in the economically more developed regions.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Switzerland, which lacked a central court or academy, the Enlightenment spread through the intellectual elite of reformed cities, particularly pastors educated in academies and colleges with strong humanist traditions.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Swiss Enlightenment thinkers made significant contributions across multiple fields.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In literature, Johann Jakob Bodmer and Johann Jakob Breitinger made Zurich a center of German literary innovation, while Albert von Haller's poetry represented the peak of Swiss Enlightenment literature.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Jean-Jacques Rousseau, considering himself both a Genevan and Swiss citizen, developed democratic republican theories that extended Genevan models to broader European federalist principles.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement was characterized by what scholars term "Helvetism" – specifically Swiss aspects including a Christian conception of natural law, patriotic ethics, and philosophical approaches grounded in practical pedagogy and economics.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Most distinctively, Swiss Enlightenment thought celebrated Alpine nature, viewing Switzerland as the "land of shepherds" whose republican and federalist traditions were shaped by its mountain environment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement organized through numerous societies and publications, including the *Encyclopédie d'Yverdon* (1770-1780), which offered a moderate alternative to the French *Encyclopédie*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Swiss intellectuals gained international prominence, with many serving in foreign academies, particularly in Berlin under Frederick II and in St.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Italy, the main centers of diffusion of the Enlightenment were Naples and Milan: in both cities the intellectuals took public office and collaborated with the Bourbon and Habsburg administrations.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Naples, Antonio Genovesi, Ferdinando Galiani, and Gaetano Filangieri were active under the tolerant King Charles of Bourbon.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, the Neapolitan Enlightenment, like Vico's philosophy, remained almost always in the theoretical field.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Only later, many Enlighteners animated the unfortunate experience of the Parthenopean Republic.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Milan, however, the movement strove to find concrete solutions to problems.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The center of discussions was the magazine *Il Caffè* (1762–1766), founded by brothers Pietro and Alessandro Verri (famous philosophers and writers, as well as their brother Giovanni), who also gave life to the Accademia dei Pugni, founded in 1761.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Minor centers were Tuscany, Veneto, and Piedmont, where among others, Pompeo Neri worked.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] From Naples, Genovesi influenced a generation of southern Italian intellectuals and university students.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] His textbook *Della diceosina, o sia della Filosofia del Giusto e dell'Onesto* (1766) was a controversial attempt to mediate between the history of moral philosophy on the one hand and the specific problems encountered by 18th-century commercial society on the other.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] It contained the greater part of Genovesi's political, philosophical, and economic thought, which became a guidebook for Neapolitan economic and social development.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Science flourished as Alessandro Volta and Luigi Galvani made break-through discoveries in electricity.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Pietro Verri was a leading economist in Lombardy.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Historian Joseph Schumpeter states he was "the most important pre-Smithian authority on Cheapness-and-Plenty." The most influential scholar on the Italian Enlightenment has been Franco Venturi.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Italy also produced some of the Enlightenment's greatest legal theorists, including Cesare Beccaria, Giambattista Vico, and Francesco Mario Pagano.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] When Charles II, the last Spanish Habsburg monarch, died his successor was from the French House of Bourbon, initiating a period of French Enlightenment influence in Spain and the Spanish Empire.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In the 18th Century, the Spanish continued to expand their empire in the Americas with the Spanish missions in California and established missions deeper inland in South America.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Under Charles III, the crown began to implement serious structural changes.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The monarchy curtailed the power of the Catholic Church, and established a standing military in Spanish America.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Freer trade was promoted under *comercio libre* in which regions could trade with companies sailing from any other Spanish port, rather than the restrictive mercantile system.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The crown sent out scientific expeditions to assert Spanish sovereignty over territories it claimed but did not control, but also importantly to discover the economic potential of its far-flung empire.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Botanical expeditions sought plants that could be of use to the empire.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Charles IV gave Prussian scientist Alexander von Humboldt free rein to travel in Spanish America, usually closed to foreigners, and more importantly, access to crown officials to aid the success of his scientific expedition.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] When Napoleon invaded Spain in 1808, Ferdinand VII abdicated and Napoleon placed his brother Joseph Bonaparte on the throne.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] To add legitimacy to this move, the Bayonne Constitution was promulgated, which included representation from Spain's overseas components, but most Spaniards rejected the whole Napoleonic project.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Cortes de Cádiz (parliament) was convened to rule Spain in the absence of the legitimate monarch, Ferdinand.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The constitution was in effect from 1812 until 1814, when Napoleon was defeated and Ferdinand was restored to the throne of Spain.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Upon his return, Ferdinand repudiated the constitution and reestablished absolutist rule.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Haitian Revolution began in 1791 and ended in 1804 and shows how Enlightenment ideas "were part of complex transcultural flows." Radical ideas in Paris during and after the French Revolution were mobilized in Haiti, such as by Toussaint Louverture.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Portuguese Enlightenment was heavily marked by the rule of Prime Minister Marquis of Pombal under King Joseph I from 1756 to 1777.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] His urbanistic ideas, also being the first large-scale example of earthquake engineering, became collectively known as Pombaline style, and were implemented throughout the kingdom during his stay in office.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] His governance was as enlightened as ruthless, see for example the Távora affair.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In literature, the first Enlightenment ideas in Portugal can be traced back to the diplomat, philosopher, and writer António Vieira who spent a considerable amount of his life in colonial Brazil denouncing discriminations against New Christians and the indigenous peoples in Brazil.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During the 18th century, enlightened literary movements such as the Arcádia Lusitana (lasting from 1756 until 1776, then replaced by the Nova Arcádia in 1790 until 1794) surfaced in the academic medium, in particular involving former students of the University of Coimbra.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] A distinct member of this group was the poet Manuel Maria Barbosa du Bocage.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The physician António Nunes Ribeiro Sanches was also an important Enlightenment figure, contributing to the *Encyclopédie* and being part of the Russian court.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The ideas of the Enlightenment influenced various economists and anti-colonial intellectuals throughout the Portuguese Empire, such as José de Azeredo Coutinho, José da Silva Lisboa, Cláudio Manoel da Costa, and Tomás Antônio Gonzaga.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Napoleonic invasion of Portugal had consequences for the Portuguese monarchy.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] With the aid of the British navy, the Portuguese royal family was evacuated to Brazil, its most important colony.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Even though Napoleon had been defeated, the royal court remained in Brazil.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Liberal Revolution of 1820 forced the return of the royal family to Portugal.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The terms by which the restored king was to rule was a constitutional monarchy under the Constitution of Portugal.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Brazil declared its independence from Portugal in 1822 and became a monarchy.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The existence of a Swedish Enlightenment has been debated by scholars.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Between 1718 and 1772, the Swedish Enlightenment overlapped with the period of parliamentary rule known in Swedish history as the Age of Liberty.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Russia, the government began to actively encourage the proliferation of arts and sciences in the mid-18th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] This era produced the first Russian university, library, theatre, public museum, and independent press.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Like other enlightened despots, Catherine the Great played a key role in fostering the arts, sciences and education.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] She used her own interpretation of Enlightenment ideals, assisted by notable international experts such as Voltaire (by correspondence) and in residence world class scientists such as Leonhard Euler and Peter Simon Pallas.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The national Enlightenment differed from its Western European counterpart in that it promoted further modernization of all aspects of Russian life and was concerned with attacking the institution of serfdom in Russia.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Russian Enlightenment centered on the individual instead of societal enlightenment and encouraged the living of an enlightened life.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] A powerful element was *prosveshchenie* which combined religious piety, erudition, and commitment to the spread of learning.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, it lacked the skeptical and critical spirit of the Western European Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Enlightenment ideas (*oświecenie*) emerged late in Poland, as the Polish middle class was weaker and szlachta (nobility) culture (Sarmatism) together with the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth political system (Golden Liberty) were in deep crisis.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The political system was built on aristocratic republicanism, but was unable to defend itself against powerful neighbors Russia, Prussia, and Austria as they repeatedly sliced off regions until nothing was left of independent Poland.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Polish Enlightenment began in the 1730s–40s and especially in theatre and the arts peaked in the reign of King Stanisław August Poniatowski (second half of the 18th century).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Warsaw was a main centre after 1750, with an expansion of schools and educational institutions and the arts patronage held at the Royal Castle.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Leaders promoted tolerance and more education.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] They included King Stanislaw II August and reformers Piotr Switkowski, Antoni Poplawski, Josef Niemcewicz, and Jósef Pawlinkowski, as well as Baudouin de Cortenay, a Polonized dramatist.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Opponents included Florian Jaroszewicz, Gracjan Piotrowski, Karol Wyrwicz, and Wojciech Skarszewski.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement went into decline with the Third Partition of Poland (1795) – a national tragedy inspiring a short period of sentimental writing – and ended in 1822, replaced by Romanticism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] From 1641 to 1853, the Tokugawa shogunate of Japan enforced a policy called *kaikin.* The policy prohibited foreign contact with most outside countries.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During this time, Korea "aimed at isolation" and was known as the "hermit kingdom" but became awakened to Enlightenment ideas by the 1890s such as with the activities of the Independence Club.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Korea was influenced by China and Japan but also found its own Enlightenment path with the Korean intellectual Yu Kilchun who popularized the term Enlightenment throughout Korea.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In 18th-century India, Tipu Sultan was an enlightened monarch, who "was one of the founding members of the (French) Jacobin Club in Seringapatam, had planted a liberty tree, and asked to be addressed as 'Tipu Citoyen,'" which means Citizen Tipu.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In parts of India, an important movement called the "Bengal Renaissance" led to Enlightenment reforms beginning in the 1820s.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Enlightenment began to influence the Ottoman Empire in the 1830s and continued into the late 19th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Tanzimat was a period of reform in the Ottoman Empire that began with the Gülhane Hatt-ı Şerif in 1839 and ended with the First Constitutional Era in 1876.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Arab Enlightenment, or *Nahda* (Arabic: النّهضة, "the awakening"), was a cultural movement in Arab-populated regions of the Ottoman Empire such as Egypt, Lebanon, Syria, and Tunisia, during the second half of the 19th century and the early 20th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The *Nahda* is often traced to the cultural shock of the French invasion of Egypt and Syria in 1798, and the reformist drive of subsequent rulers such as Muhammad Ali of Egypt.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The idea of the Enlightenment has always been contested territory.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] According to Keith Thomas, its supporters "hail it as the source of everything that is progressive about the modern world.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] From the start, conservative and clerical defenders of traditional religion attacked materialism and skepticism as evil forces that encouraged immorality.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] By 1794, they pointed to the Reign of Terror during the French Revolution as confirmation of their predictions.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Romantic philosophers argued that the Enlightenment's excessive dependence on reason was a mistake that it perpetuated, disregarding the bonds of history, myth, faith, and tradition that were necessary to hold society together.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Ritchie Robertson portrays it as a grand intellectual and political program, offering a "science" of society modeled on the powerful physical laws of Newton.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] "Social science" was seen as the instrument of human improvement.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] It would expose truth and expand human happiness.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The rights of women and non-White people were generally overlooked in Enlightenment philosophy, which is often explicitly Eurocentric.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Scientific racism first emerged at this time, bringing together traditional racism and new research methods.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During the Enlightenment, concepts of monogenism and polygenism became popular, though they would only be systematized epistemologically during the 19th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Monogenism contends that all races have a single origin, while polygenism is the idea that each race has a separate origin.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Until the 18th century, the words "race" and "species" were interchangeable.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The classification of non-European peoples as sub-human and irrational served to justify European dominance.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The term "Enlightenment" emerged in English in the latter part of the 19th century, with particular reference to French philosophy, as the equivalent of the French term *Lumières* (used first by Jean-Baptiste Dubos in 1733 and already well established by 1751).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] From Kant's 1784 essay "Beantwortung der Frage: Was ist Aufklärung?" ("Answering the Question: What is Enlightenment?"), the German term became *Aufklärung* (*aufklären* = to illuminate; *sich aufklären* = to clear up).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, scholars have never agreed on a definition of the Enlightenment or on its chronological or geographical extent.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Terms like *les Lumières* (French), *illuminism*o (Italian), *ilustración* (Spanish) and *Aufklärung* (German) referred to partly overlapping movements.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Enlightenment historiography began in the period itself, from what Enlightenment figures said about their work.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] A dominant element was the intellectual angle they took.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Jean le Rond d'Alembert's *Preliminary Discourse* of *l'Encyclopédie* provides a history of the Enlightenment which comprises a chronological list of developments in the realm of knowledge—of which the *Encyclopédie* forms the pinnacle.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In 1783, Mendelssohn referred to Enlightenment as a process by which man was educated in the use of reason.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Bertrand Russell saw the Enlightenment as a phase in a progressive development which began in antiquity and that reason and challenges to the established order were constant ideals throughout that time.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Although many of these philosophical ideals were picked up by Catholics, Russell argues that by the 18th century the Enlightenment was the principal manifestation of the schism that began with Martin Luther.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Jonathan Israel rejects the attempts of postmodern and Marxian historians to understand the revolutionary ideas of the period purely as by-products of social and economic transformations.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] He instead focuses on the history of ideas in the period from 1650 to the end of the 18th century and claims that it was the ideas themselves that caused the change that eventually led to the revolutions of the latter half of the 18th century and the early 19th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] There is little consensus on the beginning of the Enlightenment, though several historians and philosophers argue that it was marked by Descartes' 1637 philosophy of *Cogito, ergo sum* ("I think, therefore I am"), which shifted the epistemological basis from external authority to internal certainty.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In France, many cited the publication of Newton's *Principia Mathematica* (1687), which built upon the work of earlier scientists and formulated the laws of motion and universal gravitation.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] French historians usually place the *Siècle des Lumières* ("Century of Enlightenments") between 1715 and 1789: from the beginning of the reign of Louis XV until the French Revolution.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Most scholars use the last years of the century, often choosing the French Revolution or the beginning of the Napoleonic Wars (1804) as a convenient point in time with which to date the end of the Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In their 1947 book *Dialectic of Enlightenment,* Frankfurt School philosophers Max Horkheimer and Theodor W.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Extending Horkheimer and Adorno's argument, intellectual historian Jason Josephson Storm argues that any idea of the Enlightenment as a clearly defined period that is separate from the earlier Renaissance and later Romanticism or Counter-Enlightenment constitutes a myth.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Storm defends his categorization of the Enlightenment as "myth" by noting the regulative role ideas of a period of Enlightenment and disenchantment play in modern Western culture, such that belief in magic, spiritualism, and even religion appears somewhat taboo in intellectual strata.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In the 1970s, study of the Enlightenment expanded to include the ways Enlightenment ideas spread to European colonies and how they interacted with indigenous cultures and how the Enlightenment took place in formerly unstudied areas such as Italy, Greece, the Balkans, Poland, Hungary, and Russia.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Intellectuals such as Robert Darnton and Jürgen Habermas have focused on the social conditions of the Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Habermas described the creation of the "bourgeois public sphere" in 18th-century Europe, containing the new venues and modes of communication allowing for rational exchange.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Habermas said that the public sphere was bourgeois, egalitarian, rational, and independent from the state, making it the ideal venue for intellectuals to critically examine contemporary politics and society, away from the interference of established authority.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p02] While the public sphere is generally an integral component of the social study of the Enlightenment, other historians have questioned whether the public sphere had these characteristics.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This approach studies the process of changing sociabilities and cultural practices during the Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Elements of the public sphere included that it was egalitarian, that it discussed the domain of "common concern," and that argument was founded on reason.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Habermas uses the term "common concern" to describe those areas of political/social knowledge and discussion that were previously the exclusive territory of the state and religious authorities, now open to critical examination by the public sphere.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The values of this bourgeois public sphere included holding reason to be supreme, considering everything to be open to criticism (the public sphere is critical), and the opposition of secrecy of all sorts.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The creation of the public sphere has been associated with two long-term historical trends: the rise of the modern nation state and the rise of capitalism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The modern nation state in its consolidation of public power created by counterpoint a private realm of society independent of the state, which allowed for the public sphere.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Capitalism also increased society's autonomy and self-awareness, as well as an increasing need for the exchange of information.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As the nascent public sphere expanded, it embraced a large variety of institutions, and the most commonly cited were coffee houses and cafés, salons and the literary public sphere, figuratively localized in the Republic of Letters.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In France, the creation of the public sphere was helped by the aristocracy's move from the king's palace at Versailles to Paris in about 1720, since their rich spending stimulated the trade in luxuries and artistic creations, especially fine paintings.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The word "public" implies the highest level of inclusivity—the public sphere by definition should be open to all.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, this sphere was only public to relative degrees.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Cross-class influences occurred through noble and lower class participation in areas such as the coffeehouses and the Masonic lodges.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Because of the focus on reason over superstition, the Enlightenment cultivated the arts.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Emphasis on learning, art, and music became more widespread, especially with the growing middle class.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Areas of study such as literature, philosophy, science, and the fine arts increasingly explored subject matter to which the general public, in addition to the previously more segregated professionals and patrons, could relate.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As musicians depended more on public support, public concerts became increasingly popular and helped supplement performers' and composers' incomes.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The concerts also helped them to reach a wider audience.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Handel, for example, epitomized this with his highly public musical activities in London.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] He gained considerable fame there with performances of his operas and oratorios.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The music of Haydn and Mozart, with their Viennese Classical styles, are usually regarded as being the most in line with the Enlightenment ideals.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The desire to explore, record, and systematize knowledge had a meaningful impact on music publications.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Rousseau's *Dictionnaire de musique* (published 1767 in Geneva and 1768 in Paris) was a leading text in the late 18th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This widely available dictionary gave short definitions of words like genius and taste and was clearly influenced by the Enlightenment movement.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Another text influenced by Enlightenment values was Charles Burney's *A General History of Music: From the Earliest Ages to the Present Period* (1776), which was a historical survey and an attempt to rationalize elements in music systematically over time.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Recently, musicologists have shown renewed interest in the ideas and consequences of the Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As the economy and the middle class expanded, there was an increasing number of amateur musicians.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] One manifestation of this involved women, who became more involved with music on a social level.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Women were already engaged in professional roles as singers and increased their presence in the amateur performers' scene, especially with keyboard music.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Music publishers began to print music that amateurs could understand and play.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The majority of the works that were published were for keyboard, voice and keyboard, and chamber ensemble.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] After these initial genres were popularized, from the mid-century on, amateur groups sang choral music, which then became a new trend for publishers to capitalize on.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The increasing study of the fine arts, as well as access to amateur-friendly published works, led to more people becoming interested in reading and discussing music.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Music magazines, reviews, and critical works which suited amateurs as well as connoisseurs began to surface.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The *philosophes* spent a great deal of energy disseminating their ideas among educated men and women in cosmopolitan cities.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They used many venues, some of them quite new.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Republic of Letters was the sum of a number of Enlightenment ideals: an egalitarian realm governed by knowledge that could act across political boundaries and rival state power.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was a forum that supported "free public examination of questions regarding religion or legislation." Kant considered written communication essential to his conception of the public sphere; once everyone was a part of the "reading public," then society could be said to be enlightened.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The people who participated in the Republic of Letters, such as Diderot and Voltaire, are frequently known today as important Enlightenment figures.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] While women were marginalized in the public culture of the Old Regime, the French Revolution destroyed the old cultural and economic restraints of patronage and corporatism (medieval guilds), opening French society to female participation, particularly in the literary sphere.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In France, the established men of letters (*gens de lettres*) had fused with the elites (*les grands*) of French society by the mid-18th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was Grub Street literature that was most read by the public during the Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] According to Darnton, more importantly the Grub Street hacks inherited the "revolutionary spirit" once displayed by the *philosophes* and paved the way for the French Revolution by desacralizing figures of political, moral, and religious authority in France.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The increased consumption of reading materials of all sorts was one of the key features of the "social" Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, demand for reading material extended outside of the realm of the commercial and outside the realm of the upper and middle classes, as evidenced by the bibliothèque bleue.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Literacy rates are difficult to gauge, but in France the rates doubled over the course of the 18th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Reflecting the decreasing influence of religion, the number of books about science and art published in Paris doubled from 1720 to 1780, while the number of books about religion dropped to just one-tenth of the total.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Reading underwent serious changes in the 18th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In particular, Rolf Engelsing has argued for the existence of a *reading revolution.* Until 1750, reading was done intensively: people tended to own a small number of books and read them repeatedly, often to small audience.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] After 1750, people began to read "extensively," finding as many books as they could, increasingly reading them alone.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This is supported by increasing literacy rates, particularly among women.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The vast majority of the reading public could not afford to own a private library, and while most of the state-run "universal libraries" set up in the 17th and 18th centuries were open to the public, they were not the only sources of reading material.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] On one end of the spectrum was the *bibliothèque bleue,* a collection of cheaply produced books published in Troyes, France.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Intended for a largely rural and semi-literate audience these books included almanacs, retellings of medieval romances and condensed versions of popular novels, among other things.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] While some historians have argued against the Enlightenment's penetration into the lower classes, the *bibliothèque bleue* represents at least a desire to participate in Enlightenment sociability.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Moving up the classes, a variety of institutions offered readers access to material without needing to buy anything.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Libraries that lent out their material for a small price started to appear, and occasionally bookstores would offer a small lending library to their patrons.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffee houses commonly offered books, journals, and sometimes even popular novels to their customers.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] *Tatler* and *The Spectator,* two influential periodicals sold from 1709 to 1714, were closely associated with coffee house culture in London, being both read and produced in various establishments in the city.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This is an example of the triple or even quadruple function of the coffee house: reading material was often obtained, read, discussed, and even produced on the premises.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It is difficult to determine what people actually read during the Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, examining the catalogs of private libraries gives an image skewed in favor of the classes wealthy enough to afford libraries and also ignores censored works unlikely to be publicly acknowledged.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For this reason, a study of publishing would be much more fruitful for discerning reading habits.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Across continental Europe, but in France especially, booksellers and publishers had to negotiate censorship laws of varying strictness.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, the *Encyclopédie* narrowly escaped seizure and had to be saved by Malesherbes, the man in charge of the French censor.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Indeed, many publishing companies were conveniently located outside France so as to avoid overzealous French censors.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They would smuggle their merchandise across the border, where it would then be transported to clandestine booksellers or small-time peddlers.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The records of clandestine booksellers may give a better representation of what literate Frenchmen might have truly read, since their clandestine nature provided a less restrictive product choice.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In one case, political books were the most popular category, primarily libels and pamphlets.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Readers were more interested in sensationalist stories about criminals and political corruption than they were in political theory itself.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The second most popular category, "general works" (those books "that did not have a dominant motif and that contained something to offend almost everyone in authority"), demonstrated a high demand for generally low-brow subversive literature.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, these works never became part of literary canon and are largely forgotten today as a result.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] A healthy, legal publishing industry existed throughout Europe, although established publishers and book sellers occasionally ran afoul of the law.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, the *Encyclopédie*, condemned by both the King and Clement XII, nevertheless found its way into print with the help of the aforementioned Malesherbes and creative use of French censorship law.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, many works were sold without running into any legal trouble at all.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Borrowing records from libraries in England, Germany, and North America indicate that more than 70% of books borrowed were novels.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Less than 1% of the books were of a religious nature, indicating the general trend of declining religiosity.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] A genre that greatly rose in importance was that of scientific literature.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Natural history in particular became increasingly popular among the upper classes.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Works of natural history include René-Antoine Ferchault de Réaumur's *Histoire naturelle des insectes* and Jacques Gautier d'Agoty's *La Myologie complète, ou description de tous les muscles du corps humain* (1746).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Outside Ancien Régime France, natural history was an important part of medicine and industry, encompassing the fields of botany, zoology, meteorology, hydrology, and mineralogy.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Students in Enlightenment universities and academies were taught these subjects to prepare them for careers as diverse as medicine and theology.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As shown by Matthew Daniel Eddy, natural history in this context was a very middle class pursuit and operated as a fertile trading zone for the interdisciplinary exchange of diverse scientific ideas.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The target audience of natural history was French upper class, evidenced more by the specific discourse of the genre than by the generally high prices of its works.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Naturalists catered to upper class desire for erudition: many texts had an explicit instructive purpose.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, natural history was often a political affair.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In this way, natural history spread many of the scientific developments of the time but also provided a new source of legitimacy for the dominant class.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] From this basis, naturalists could then develop their own social ideals based on their scientific works.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first scientific and literary journals were established during the Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first journal, the Parisian *Journal des sçavans*, appeared in 1665.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, it was not until 1682 that periodicals began to be more widely produced.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] French and Latin were the dominant languages of publication, but there was also a steady demand for material in German and Dutch.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] There was generally low demand for English publications on the continent, which was echoed by England's similar lack of desire for French works.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Languages commanding less of an international market—such as Danish, Spanish, and Portuguese—found journal success more difficult, and a more international language was used instead.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] French slowly took over Latin's status as the *lingua franca* of learned circles.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This in turn gave precedence to the publishing industry in Holland, where the vast majority of these French language periodicals were produced.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Jonathan Israel called the journals the most influential cultural innovation of European intellectual culture.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They shifted the attention of the "cultivated public" away from established authorities to novelty and innovation, and instead promoted the Enlightened ideals of toleration and intellectual objectivity.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Being a source of knowledge derived from science and reason, they were an implicit critique of existing notions of universal truth monopolized by monarchies, parliaments, and religious authorities.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They also advanced Christian Enlightenment that upheld "the legitimacy of God-ordained authority"—the Bible—in which there had to be agreement between the biblical and natural theories.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Although the existence of dictionaries and encyclopedias spanned into ancient times, the texts changed from defining words in a long running list to far more detailed discussions of those words in 18th-century encyclopedic dictionaries.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The works were part of an Enlightenment movement to systematize knowledge and provide education to a wider audience than the elite.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As the 18th century progressed, the content of encyclopedias also changed according to readers' tastes.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Volumes tended to focus more strongly on secular affairs, particularly science and technology, rather than matters of theology.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Along with secular matters, readers also favoured an alphabetical ordering scheme over cumbersome works arranged along thematic lines.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Encyclopedias and dictionaries also became more popular during the Enlightenment as the number of educated consumers who could afford such texts began to multiply.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In the latter half of the 18th century, the number of dictionaries and encyclopedias published by decade increased from 63 between 1760 and 1769 to approximately 148 in the decade proceeding the French Revolution.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Along with growth in numbers, dictionaries and encyclopedias also grew in length, often having multiple print runs that sometimes included in supplemented editions.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first technical dictionary was drafted by John Harris and entitled *Lexicon Technicum: Or, An Universal English Dictionary of Arts and Sciences.* Harris' book avoids theological and biographical entries and instead concentrates on science and technology.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Published in 1704, the *Lexicon Technicum* was the first book to be written in English that took a methodical approach to describing mathematics and commercial arithmetic along with the physical sciences and navigation.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Other technical dictionaries followed Harris' model, including Ephraim Chambers' *Cyclopaedia* (1728), which included five editions and is a substantially larger work than Harris'.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The folio edition of the work even included foldout engravings.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The *Cyclopaedia* emphasized Newtonian theories, Lockean philosophy and contained thorough examinations of technologies, such as engraving, brewing, and dyeing.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In Germany, practical reference works intended for the uneducated majority became popular in the 18th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The *Marperger Curieuses Natur-, Kunst-, Berg-, Gewerk- und Handlungs-Lexicon* (1712) explained terms that usefully described the trades and scientific and commercial education.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] *Jablonksi Allgemeines Lexicon* (1721) was better known than the *Handlungs-Lexicon* and underscored technical subjects rather than scientific theory.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, over five columns of text were dedicated to wine while geometry and logic were allocated only twenty-two and seventeen lines, respectively.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first edition of the *Encyclopædia Britannica* (1771) was modelled along the same lines as the German lexicons.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, the prime example of reference works that systematized scientific knowledge in the Enlightenment were universal encyclopedias rather than technical dictionaries.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was the goal of universal encyclopedias to record all human knowledge in a comprehensive reference work.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The most well-known of these works is Diderot and d'Alembert's *Encyclopédie, ou dictionnaire raisonné des sciences, des arts et des métiers.* The work, which began publication in 1751, was composed of 35 volumes and over 71,000 separate entries.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] A great number of the entries were dedicated to describing the sciences and crafts in detail and provided intellectuals across Europe with a high-quality survey of human knowledge.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The massive work was arranged according to a "tree of knowledge." The tree reflected the marked division between the arts and sciences, which was largely a result of the rise of empiricism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Both areas of knowledge were united by philosophy, or the trunk of the tree of knowledge.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Enlightenment's desacrilization of religion was pronounced in the tree's design, particularly where theology accounted for a peripheral branch, with black magic as a close neighbour.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As the *Encyclopédie* gained popularity, it was published in quarto and octavo editions after 1777.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The quarto and octavo editions were much less expensive than previous editions, making the *Encyclopédie* more accessible to the non-elite.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Robert Darnton estimates that there were approximately 25,000 copies of the *Encyclopédie* in circulation throughout France and Europe before the French Revolution.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The extensive yet affordable encyclopedia came to represent the transmission of Enlightenment and scientific education to an expanding audience.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] One of the most important developments that the Enlightenment era brought to the discipline of science was its popularization.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] An increasingly literate population seeking knowledge and education in both the arts and the sciences drove the expansion of print culture and the dissemination of scientific learning.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The new literate population was precipitated by a high rise in the availability of food; this enabled many people to rise out of poverty, and instead of paying more for food, they had money for education.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] More formal works included explanations of scientific theories for individuals lacking the educational background to comprehend the original scientific text.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Newton's celebrated *Philosophiae Naturalis Principia Mathematica* was published in Latin and remained inaccessible to readers without education in the classics until Enlightenment writers began to translate and analyze the text in the vernacular.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first significant work that expressed scientific theory and knowledge expressly for the laity, in the vernacular and with the entertainment of readers in mind, was Bernard de Fontenelle's *Conversations on the Plurality of Worlds* (1686).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The book was produced specifically for women with an interest in scientific writing and inspired a variety of similar works.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These popular works were written in a discursive style, which was laid out much more clearly for the reader than the complicated articles, treatises, and books published by the academies and scientists.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Writing for a growing female audience, Francesco Algarotti published *Il Newtonianism per le dame*, which was a tremendously popular work and was translated from Italian into English by Elizabeth Carter.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] A similar introduction to Newtonianism for women was produced by Henry Pemberton.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] His *A View of Sir Isaac Newton's Philosophy* was published by subscription.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Extant records of subscribers show that women from a wide range of social standings purchased the book, indicating the growing number of scientifically inclined female readers among the middling class.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] During the Enlightenment, women also began producing popular scientific works.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Sarah Trimmer wrote a successful natural history textbook for children titled *The Easy Introduction to the Knowledge of Nature* (1782), which was published for many years in eleven editions.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Most work on the Enlightenment emphasizes the ideals discussed by intellectuals, rather than the actual state of education at the time.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Leading educational theorists like England's John Locke and Switzerland's Jean Jacques Rousseau both emphasized the importance of shaping young minds early.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] By the late Enlightenment, there was a rising demand for a more universal approach to education, particularly after the American Revolution and the French Revolution.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The predominant educational psychology from the 1750s onward, especially in northern European countries, was associationism: the notion that the mind associates or dissociates ideas through repeated routines.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Children were taught to memorize facts through oral and graphic methods that originated during the Renaissance.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Many of the leading universities associated with Enlightenment progressive principles were located in northern Europe, with the most renowned being the universities of Leiden, Göttingen, Halle, Montpellier, Uppsala, and Edinburgh.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These universities, especially Edinburgh, produced professors whose ideas had a significant impact on Britain's North American colonies and later the American Republic.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Within the natural sciences, Edinburgh's medical school also led the way in chemistry, anatomy, and pharmacology.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In other parts of Europe, the universities and schools of France and most of Europe were bastions of traditionalism and were not hospitable to the Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In France, the major exception was the medical university at Montpellier.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The history of Academies in France during the Enlightenment begins with the Academy of Science, founded in 1666 in Paris.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was closely tied to the French state, acting as an extension of a government seriously lacking in scientists.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It helped promote and organize new disciplines and it trained new scientists.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It also contributed to the enhancement of scientists' social status, considering them to be the "most useful of all citizens." Academies demonstrate the rising interest in science along with its increasing secularization, as evidenced by the small number of clerics who were members (13%).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The presence of the French academies in the public sphere cannot be attributed to their membership, as although the majority of their members were bourgeois, the exclusive institution was only open to elite Parisian scholars.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They perceived themselves as "interpreters of the sciences for the people." For example, it was with this in mind that academicians took it upon themselves to disprove the popular pseudo-science of mesmerism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The strongest contribution of the French Academies to the public sphere comes from the *concours académiques* (roughly translated as "academic contests") they sponsored throughout France.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These academic contests were perhaps the most public of any institution during the Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The practice of contests dated back to the Middle Ages and was revived in the mid-17th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The subject matter had previously been generally religious and/or monarchical, featuring essays, poetry, and painting.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] More importantly, the contests were open to all, and the enforced anonymity of each submission guaranteed that neither gender nor social rank would determine the judging.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Indeed, although the "vast majority" of participants belonged to the wealthier strata of society ("the liberal arts, the clergy, the judiciary and the medical profession"), there were some cases of the popular classes submitting essays and even winning.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Similarly, a significant number of women participated—and won—the competitions.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Of a total of 2,300 prize competitions offered in France, women won 49—perhaps a small number by modern standards but very significant in an age in which very few women had any academic training.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Indeed, the majority of the winning entries were for poetry competitions, a genre commonly stressed in women's education.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In England, the Royal Society of London played a significant role in the public sphere and the spread of Enlightenment ideas.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was founded by a group of independent scientists and given a royal charter in 1662.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The society played a large role in spreading Robert Boyle's experimental philosophy around Europe and acted as a clearinghouse for intellectual correspondence and exchange.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Boyle was "a founder of the experimental world in which scientists now live and operate" and his method based knowledge on experimentation, which had to be witnessed to provide proper empirical legitimacy.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This is where the Royal Society came into play: witnessing had to be a "collective act" and the Royal Society's assembly rooms were ideal locations for relatively public demonstrations.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Salons were places where *philosophes* were reunited and discussed old, actual, or new ideas.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This led to salons being the birthplace of intellectual and enlightened ideas.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffeehouses were especially important to the spread of knowledge during the Enlightenment because they created a unique environment in which people from many different walks of life gathered and shared ideas.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They were frequently criticized by nobles who feared the possibility of an environment in which class and its accompanying titles and privileges were disregarded.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Such an environment was especially intimidating to monarchs who derived much of their power from the disparity between classes of people.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] If the different classes joined together under the influence of Enlightenment thinking, they might recognize the all-encompassing oppression and abuses of their monarchs and because of the numbers of their members might be able to successfully revolt.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Monarchs also resented the idea of their subjects convening as one to discuss political matters, especially matters of foreign affairs.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Rulers thought political affairs were their business only, a result of their divine right to rule.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffeeshops became homes away from home for many who sought to engage in discourse with their neighbors and discuss intriguing and thought-provoking matters, from philosophy to politics.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffeehouses were essential to the Enlightenment, for they were centers of free-thinking and self-discovery.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Although many coffeehouse patrons were scholars, many were not.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffeehouses attracted a diverse set of people, including the educated wealthy and bourgeois as well as the lower classes.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Patrons, being doctors, lawyers, merchants, represented almost all classes, so the coffeeshop environment sparked fear in those who wanted to preserve class distinction.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] One of the most popular critiques of the coffeehouse said that it "allowed promiscuous association among people from different rungs of the social ladder, from the artisan to the aristocrat" and was therefore compared to Noah's Ark, receiving all types of animals, clean and unclean.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This unique culture served as a catalyst for journalism, when Joseph Addison and Richard Steele recognized its potential as an audience.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Together, Steele and Addison published *The Spectator (1711)*, a daily publication which aimed, through fictional narrator Mr.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Spectator, to both entertain and provoke discussion on serious philosophical matters.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first English coffeehouse opened in Oxford in 1650.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Brian Cowan said that Oxford coffeehouses developed into "penny universities," offering a locus of learning that was less formal than at structured institutions.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These penny universities occupied a significant position in Oxford academic life, as they were frequented by those consequently referred to as the *virtuosi,* who conducted their research on some of the premises.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Café Procope was established in Paris in 1686, and by the 1720s there were around 400 cafés in the city.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Café Procope in particular became a center of Enlightenment, welcoming such celebrities as Voltaire and Rousseau.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Café Procope was where Diderot and D'Alembert decided to create the *Encyclopédie*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The cafés were one of the various "nerve centers" for *bruits publics,* public noise or rumour.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These *bruits* were allegedly a much better source of information than were the actual newspapers available at the time.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The debating societies are an example of the public sphere during the Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In the late 1770s, popular debating societies began to move into more "genteel" rooms, a change which helped establish a new standard of sociability.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The backdrop to these developments was "an explosion of interest in the theory and practice of public elocution." The debating societies were commercial enterprises that responded to this demand, sometimes very successfully.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Some societies welcomed from 800 to 1,200 spectators per night.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The debating societies discussed an extremely wide range of topics.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In addition to debates on religion, societies discussed issues such as politics and the role of women.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, the critical subject matter of these debates did not necessarily translate into opposition to the government; the results of the debate quite frequently upheld the *status quo*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] From a historical standpoint, one of the most important features of the debating society was their openness to the public, as women attended and even participated in almost every debating society, which were likewise open to all classes providing they could pay the entrance fee.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Once inside, spectators were able to participate in a largely egalitarian form of sociability that helped spread Enlightenment ideas.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Historians have debated the extent to which the secret network of Freemasonry was a main factor in the Enlightenment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Leaders of the Enlightenment included Freemasons such as Diderot, Montesquieu, Voltaire, Lessing, Pope, Horace Walpole, Robert Walpole, Mozart, Goethe, Frederick the Great, Benjamin Franklin and George Washington.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Norman Davies said Freemasonry was a powerful force on behalf of liberalism in Europe from about 1700 to the twentieth century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It expanded during the Enlightenment, reaching practically every country in Europe.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was especially attractive to powerful aristocrats and politicians as well as intellectuals, artists, and political activists.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] During the Enlightenment, Freemasons comprised an international network of like-minded men, often meeting in secret in ritualistic programs at their lodges.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They promoted the ideals of the Enlightenment and helped diffuse these values across Britain, France, and other places.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Freemasonry as a systematic creed with its own myths, values, and rituals originated in Scotland c.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] 1600 and spread to England and then across the Continent in the 18th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Freemasonry was particularly prevalent in France—by 1789, there were perhaps as many as 100,000 French Masons, making Freemasonry the most popular of all Enlightenment associations.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Freemasons displayed a passion for secrecy and created new degrees and ceremonies.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Similar societies, partially imitating Freemasonry, emerged in France, Germany, Sweden, and Russia.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] One example was the Illuminati, founded in Bavaria in 1776, which was copied after the Freemasons, but was never part of the movement.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The name itself translates to "enlightened," chosen to reflect their original intent to promote the values of the movement.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Illuminati was an overtly political group, which most Masonic lodges decidedly were not.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Masonic lodges created a private model for public affairs.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They "reconstituted the polity and established a constitutional form of self-government, complete with constitutions and laws, elections, and representatives." In other words, the micro-society set up within the lodges constituted a normative model for society as a whole.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This was especially true on the continent: when the first lodges began to appear in the 1730s, their embodiment of British values was often seen as threatening by state authorities.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, the Parisian lodge that met in the mid 1720s was composed of English Jacobite exiles.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Furthermore, freemasons across Europe explicitly linked themselves to the Enlightenment as a whole.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, in French lodges the line "As the means to be enlightened I search for the enlightened" was a part of their initiation rites.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] British lodges assigned themselves the duty to "initiate the unenlightened." This did not necessarily link lodges to the irreligious, but neither did this exclude them from the occasional heresy.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In fact, many lodges praised the Grand Architect, the masonic terminology for the deistic divine being who created a scientifically ordered universe.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Diderot discusses the link between Freemason ideals and the enlightenment in D'Alembert's Dream, exploring masonry as a way of spreading enlightenment beliefs.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Historian Margaret Jacob stresses the importance of the Masons in indirectly inspiring enlightened political thought.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] On the negative side, Daniel Roche contests claims that Masonry promoted egalitarianism and he argues the lodges only attracted men of similar social backgrounds.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The presence of noble women in the French "lodges of adoption" that formed in the 1780s was largely due to the close ties shared between these lodges and aristocratic society.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The major opponent of Freemasonry was the Catholic Church so in countries with a large Catholic element, such as France, Italy, Spain, and Mexico, much of the ferocity of the political battles involve the confrontation between what Davies calls the reactionary Church and enlightened Freemasonry.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Even in France, Masons did not act as a group.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] American historians, while noting that Benjamin Franklin and George Washington were indeed active Masons, have downplayed the importance of Freemasonry in causing the American Revolution because the Masonic order was non-political and included both Patriots and their enemy the Loyalists.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/age-of-enlightenment-p03] At the same time, the classical art of Greece and Rome became interesting to people again, since archaeological teams discovered Pompeii and Herculaneum.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] Agen (Latin *Aginnum*) was the capital of the Celtic tribe of the Nitiobroges, and the discovery of extensive ruins attests its importance under the Roman Empire.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] In later times it was the capital of the Agenais region.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] Its bishopric was founded in the 4th century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] Agen changed hands more than once in the course of the Albigensian wars, and at their close a tribunal of inquisition was established in the town and inflicted cruel persecution on the heretics.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] During the religious wars of the 16th century, Agen took the part of the Catholics and openly joined the League in 1589.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The Hôtel de Ville was completed in around 1666.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The city of Agen lies in the southwestern department of Lot-et-Garonne in the Nouvelle-Aquitaine region.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The city centre lies on the east bank of the river Garonne, the Canal de Garonne flows through the city, approximately halfway between Bordeaux 132 km (82 mi) and Toulouse 107 km (66 mi).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] Agen features an oceanic climate (*Cfb*) in the Köppen climate classification and according to the latest temperature numbers borders a humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] According to the Trewartha climate classification the climate is now humid subtropical (*Cf*).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] Winters are mild and feature cool to cold temperatures while summers are mild and warm.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] Rainfall is spread equally throughout the year; however, most sunshine hours are from March–September.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] From Occitan *Agen* (1197), itself from Latin *Aginnum* (3rd century *Itinéraire d'Antonin*), from a Celtic root *agin-* meaning "rock or height".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The town has a higher level of unemployment than the national average.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] Major employers include the pharmaceutical factory UPSA.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The old centre of town contains a number of medieval buildings.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The twelfth century Agen Cathedral, dedicated to Saint Caprasius, is one of the few large churches in France with a double nave, a regional trait also found in the Church of the Jacobins in nearby Toulouse.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The Saint Hilaire church, dedicated to the theme of the Holy Trinity which the Saint in question did a lot to defend, is notable for its unusual statues in front of the Church – Moses on the right, and St Peter on the left.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The art museum, the Musée des Beaux Arts, contains artefacts, furniture and sculptures from prehistoric times onwards.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The art gallery contains several hundred works, including several by Goya, and others by Bonnard and Seurat.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The collection also contains a large number of works by artists who lived locally.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The museum is made up of twenty or so rooms.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The Canal des Deux Mers, which joins the Mediterranean with the Atlantic, crosses the river Garonne at Agen via the town's famous canal bridge.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] Louis Arthur Ducos du Hauron (1837 – 1920), a pioneer of colour photography lived and worked in Agen.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] He developed practical processes for colour photography on the three-colour principle, using both additive and subtractive methods.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] In 1868 he patented his ideas (French Patent No.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] 83061) and in 1869 he published them in *Les couleurs en photographie, solution du problème*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The most widely reproduced of his surviving colour photographs is the *View of Agen*, an 1877 landscape, printed by the subtractive assembly method which he pioneered.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] Several different photographs of the view from his attic window, one dated 1874, also survive.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The municipal theatre "Théâtre Ducourneau" presents theatre, and occasionally classical concerts.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The smaller "Théâtre du jour" has a resident theatre company presenting a variety of recent or older plays (Shakespeare, Beckett, as well as lesser known playwrights).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] There are two cinemas, one a commercial multiscreened affair, the other an arts cinema run by a voluntary organization.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The latter organizes film festivals every year.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] Rugby is extremely popular in the town, and the local team, SU Agen, is enthusiastically supported.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The town also serves as the base for the Team Lot-et-Garonne cycling team.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The Gare d'Agen connects Agen with Toulouse and Bordeaux as well as Périgueux.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] It is around an hour from Toulouse and around an hour from Bordeaux.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The TGV train to Paris takes three hours and thirteen minutes with a stop in Bordeaux.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] Agen is connected, by the A62 autoroute, to both Toulouse and Bordeaux.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The Agen Airport is serviced by Airlinair service to Paris Orly 6 days a week.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] It is also used for business and leisure flying.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] Agen stands on the *voie verte* cycle path between the Mediterranean and close to Bordeaux.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] Agen is the seat of a Roman Catholic diocese that comprises the Département of Lot and Garonne.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] It is a suffragan of the archdiocese of Bordeaux.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] Agen is the "capital of the prune", a local product consumed as a sweet, either stuffed with prune purée or in pastries, or as a dessert, e.g., prunes soaked in Armagnac, a type of brandy.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] On the last weekend of August, a prune festival comprises rock concerts, circus performances and prune tastings.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] The first Jews settled in the town in the twelfth century AD.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] They were expelled from the town in 1306.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] A number of Jews returned to the town in 1315, and a "Rue des Juifs" is documented ever since this period.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] In 1968, about 600 Jews lived in the town, though most of them had emigrated from North Africa.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/agen] A Jewish synagogue still exists in the town.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Between 1799 and 1804, Humboldt travelled extensively in the Americas, exploring and describing them for the first time from a non-Spanish European scientific point of view.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] His description of the journey was written up and published in several volumes over 21 years.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt resurrected the use of the word *cosmos* from the ancient Greek and assigned it to his multivolume treatise, *Kosmos*, in which he sought to unify diverse branches of scientific knowledge and culture.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] This important work also motivated a holistic perception of the universe as one interacting entity, which introduced concepts of ecology leading to ideas of environmentalism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] In 1800, and again in 1831, he described scientifically, on the basis of observations generated during his travels, local impacts of development causing human-induced climate change.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt is seen as "the father of ecology" and "the father of environmentalism".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Alexander von Humboldt was born in Berlin in Prussia on 14 September 1769.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] He was baptized as a baby in the Lutheran faith, with the Duke of Brunswick-Wolfenbüttel serving as godfather.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] His father, Alexander Georg von Humboldt (1720–1779), belonged to a prominent German noble family from Pomerania.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Although not one of the titled gentry, he was a major in the Prussian Army, who had served with the Duke of Brunswick.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] At age 42, Alexander Georg was rewarded for his services in the Seven Years' War with the post of royal chamberlain.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] He profited from the contract to lease state lotteries and tobacco sales.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Alexander's grandfather was Johann Paul von Humboldt (1684–1740), who married Sophia Dorothea von Schweder (1688–1749), daughter of Prussian General Adjutant Michael von Schweder (1663–1729).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] In 1766, his father, Alexander Georg married Maria Elisabeth Colomb, a well-educated woman and widow of Baron Friedrich Ernst von Holwede (1723–1765), with whom she had a son Heinrich Friedrich Ludwig (1762–1817).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Alexander Georg and Maria Elisabeth had four children: two daughters, Karoline and Gabriele, who died young, and then two sons, Wilhelm and Alexander.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Her first-born son, Wilhelm and Alexander's half-brother, Rittmaster in the Gendarme regiment was something of a ne'er-do-well, not often mentioned in the family history.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Alexander Georg died in 1779, leaving the brothers Humboldt in the care of their emotionally distant mother.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] She had high ambitions for Alexander and his older brother Wilhelm, hiring excellent tutors, who were Enlightenment thinkers, including Kantian physician Marcus Herz and botanist Carl Ludwig Willdenow, who became one of the most important botanists in Germany.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt's mother expected them to become civil servants of the Prussian state.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] The money left to Alexander's mother by Baron Holwede became instrumental in funding Alexander's explorations after her death; contributing more than 70% of his private income.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Due to his youthful penchant for collecting and labeling plants, shells, and insects, Alexander received the playful title of "the little apothecary".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Marked for a political career, Alexander studied finance for six months in 1787 at the University of Frankfurt (Oder), which his mother might have chosen less for its academic excellence than its closeness to their home in Berlin.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] On 25 April 1789, he matriculated at the University of Göttingen, then known for the lectures of C.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] His brother Wilhelm was already a student at Göttingen, but they did not interact much, since their intellectual interests were quite different.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] His vast and varied interests were by this time fully developed.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] At the University of Göttingen, Humboldt met Steven Jan van Geuns, a Dutch medical student, with whom he travelled to the Rhine in the fall of 1789.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] In Mainz, they met Georg Forster, a naturalist who had been with Captain James Cook on his second voyage.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt's scientific excursion resulted in his 1790 treatise *Mineralogische Beobachtungen über einige Basalte am Rhein* (Brunswick, 1790) (*Mineralogic Observations on Several Basalts on the River Rhine*).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] The following year, 1790, Humboldt returned to Mainz to embark with Forster on a journey to England, Humboldt's first sea voyage, the Netherlands, and France.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] In England, he met Sir Joseph Banks, president of the Royal Society, who had travelled with Captain Cook; Banks showed Humboldt his huge herbarium, with specimens of the South Sea tropics.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] The scientific friendship between Banks and Humboldt lasted until Banks's death in 1820, and the two shared botanical specimens for study.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Banks also mobilized his scientific contacts in later years to aid Humboldt's work.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] In Paris, Humboldt and Forster witnessed the preparations for the Festival of the Federation.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Yet, Humboldt's take on the French Revolution remained ambivalent.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt's passion for travel was of long standing.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] He devoted to prepare himself as a scientific explorer.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] With this emphasis, he studied commerce and foreign languages at Hamburg, geology at Freiberg School of Mines in 1791 under A.G.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Werner, leader of the Neptunist school of geology; from anatomy at Jena under J.C.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Loder; and astronomy and the use of scientific instruments under F.X. von Zach and J.G.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] During this period, his brother Wilhelm married, but Alexander did not attend the nuptials.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt graduated from the Freiberg School of Mines in 1792 and was appointed to a Prussian government position in the Department of Mines as an inspector in Bayreuth and the Fichtel Mountains.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt was excellent at his job, with production of gold ore in his first year outstripping the previous eight years.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] During his period as a mine inspector, Humboldt demonstrated his deep concern for the men laboring in the mines.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] He opened a free school for miners, paid for out of his own pocket, which became an unchartered government training school for labor.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] He also sought to establish an emergency relief fund for miners, aiding them following accidents.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt's researches into the vegetation of the mines of Freiberg led to the publication in Latin (1793) of his *Florae Fribergensis, accedunt Aphorismi ex Doctrina, Physiologiae Chemicae Plantarum*, which was a compendium of his botanical researches.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] That publication brought him to the attention of Johann Wolfgang von Goethe, who had met Humboldt at the family home when Alexander was a boy, but Goethe was now interested in meeting the young scientist to discuss metamorphism of plants.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] An introduction was arranged by Humboldt's brother, who lived in the university town of Jena, not far from Goethe.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Goethe had developed his own extensive theories on comparative anatomy.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Working before Darwin, he believed that animals had an internal force, an *urform*, that gave them a basic shape and then they were further adapted to their environment by an external force.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt urged him to publish his theories.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Together, the two discussed and expanded these ideas.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Goethe and Humboldt soon became close friends.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt often returned to Jena in the years that followed.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Goethe remarked about Humboldt to friends that he had never met anyone so versatile.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt's drive served as an inspiration for Goethe.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] In 1797, Humboldt returned to Jena for three months.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] During this time, Goethe moved from his residence in Weimar to reside in Jena.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Together, Humboldt and Goethe attended university lectures on anatomy and conducted their own experiments.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] One experiment involved hooking up a frog leg to various metals.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] They found no effect until the moisture of Humboldt's breath triggered a reaction that caused the frog leg to leap off the table.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt described this as one of his favorite experiments because it was as if he were "breathing life into" the leg.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] During this visit, a thunderstorm killed a farmer and his wife.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt obtained their corpses and analyzed them in the anatomy tower of the university.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] In 1794, Humboldt was admitted to the famous group of intellectuals and cultural leaders of Weimar Classicism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Goethe and Schiller were the key figures at the time.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] In 1792 and 1797, Humboldt was in Vienna; in 1795 he made a geological and botanical tour through Switzerland and Italy.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Neither brother attended the funeral of their mother on 19 November 1796.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt had not hidden his aversion to his mother, with one correspondent writing of him after her death, "her death... must be particularly welcomed by you".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] After severing his official connections, he awaited an opportunity to fulfill his long-cherished dream of travel.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p01] Humboldt was able to spend more time on writing up his research.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] With the financial resources to fund his scientific travels, he sought a ship on a major expedition.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In the meantime, he went to Paris, where his brother Wilhelm was living.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Paris was a great center of scientific learning and his brother and sister-in-law Caroline were well connected in those circles.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Louis-Antoine de Bougainville urged Humboldt to accompany him on a major expedition, likely to last five years, but the French revolutionary Directoire placed Nicolas Baudin at the head of it rather than the aging scientific traveler.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] On the postponement of Captain Baudin's proposed voyage of circumnavigation due to continuing warfare in Europe, which Humboldt had been officially invited to accompany, Humboldt was deeply disappointed.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He had already selected scientific instruments for his voyage.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He did, however, have a stroke of luck with meeting Aimé Bonpland, the botanist and physician for the voyage.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Discouraged, the two left Paris for Marseille, where they hoped to join Napoleon Bonaparte in Egypt, but North Africans were in revolt against the French invasion in Egypt and French authorities refused permission to travel.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt and Bonpland eventually found their way to Madrid, where their luck changed spectacularly.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In Madrid, Humboldt sought authorization to travel to Spain's realms in the Americas; he was aided in obtaining it by the German representative of Saxony at the royal Bourbon court.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Baron Forell had an interest in mineralogy and science endeavors and was inclined to help Humboldt.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] At that time, the Bourbon Reforms sought to reform administration of the realms and revitalize their economies.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] At the same time, the Spanish Enlightenment was in florescence.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] For Humboldt "the confluent effect of the Bourbon revolution in government and the Spanish Enlightenment had created ideal conditions for his venture".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The Bourbon monarchy had already authorized and funded expeditions, with the Botanical Expedition to the Viceroyalty of Peru to Chile and Peru (1777–1788), New Granada (1783–1816), New Spain (Mexico) (1787–1803), and the Malaspina Expedition (1789–1794).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] These were lengthy, state-sponsored enterprises to gather information about plants and animals from the Spanish realms, assess economic possibilities, and provide plants and seeds for the Royal Botanical Garden in Madrid (founded 1755).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] These expeditions took naturalists and artists, who created visual images as well as careful written observations as well as collecting seeds and plants themselves.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Crown officials as early as 1779 issued and systematically distributed *Instructions concerning the most secure and economic means to transport live plants by land and sea from the most distant countries*, with illustrations, including one for the crates to transport seeds and plants.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] When Humboldt requested authorization from the crown to travel to Spanish America, most importantly, with his own financing, it was given positive response.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Spain under the Habsburg monarchy had guarded its realms against foreigner travelers and intruders.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The Bourbon monarch was open to Humboldt's proposal.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Spanish Foreign Minister Don Mariano Luis de Urquijo received the formal proposal and Humboldt was presented to the monarch in March 1799.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt was granted access to crown officials and written documentation on Spain's empire.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] With Humboldt's experience working for the absolutist Prussian monarchy as a government mining official, Humboldt had both the academic training and experience of working well within a bureaucratic structure.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Before leaving Madrid in 1799, Humboldt and Bonpland visited the Natural History Museum, which held results of Martín Sessé y Lacasta and José Mariano Mociño's botanical expedition to New Spain.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt and Bonpland met Hipólito Ruiz López and José Antonio Pavón y Jiménez of the royal expedition to Peru and Chile in person in Madrid and examined their botanical collections.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Armed with authorization from the King of Spain, Humboldt and Bonpland made haste to sail, taking the ship *Pizarro* from La Coruña, on 5 June 1799.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The ship stopped six days on the island of Tenerife, where Humboldt climbed the volcano Teide, and then sailed on to the New World, landing at Cumaná, Venezuela, on 16 July.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The ship's destination was not originally Cumaná, but an outbreak of typhoid on board meant that the captain changed course from Havana to land in northern South America.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt had not mapped out a specific plan of exploration, so that the change did not upend a fixed itinerary.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He later wrote that the diversion to Venezuela made possible his explorations along the Orinoco River to the border of Portuguese Brazil.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] With the diversion, the *Pizarro* encountered two large dugout canoes each carrying 18 Guayaqui Indians.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The *Pizarro*'s captain accepted the offer of one of them to serve as pilot.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt hired this Indian, named Carlos del Pino, as a guide.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] A great deal of information on the new jurisdiction had already been compiled by François de Pons, but was not published until 1806.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] At the invitation of the captain general, Manuel de Guevara y Vasconcelos, Humboldt stayed in Caracas for about two months, leaving in February.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Rather than describe the city and its administration, Humboldt started his researches with the valley of Aragua, where export crops of sugar, coffee, cacao, and cotton were cultivated, visiting a plantation owned by the Bolívar family.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Cacao plantations were the most profitable, as world demand for chocolate rose.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] It is here that Humboldt is said to have developed his idea of human-induced climate change.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Investigating evidence of a rapid fall in the water level of the valley's Lake Valencia, Humboldt credited the desiccation to the clearance of tree cover and to the inability of the exposed soils to retain water.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] With their clear cutting of trees, the agriculturalists were removing the woodland's "threefold" moderating influence upon temperature: cooling shade, evaporation and radiation.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt visited the mission at Caripe and explored the Guácharo cavern, where he found the oilbird, which he was to make known to science as *Steatornis caripensis*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He also described the Guanoco asphalt lake as "The spring of the good priest" ("*Quelle des guten Priesters*").
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Returning to Cumaná, Humboldt observed, on the night of 11–12 November, a remarkable meteor shower (the Leonids).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He proceeded with Bonpland to Caracas where he climbed the Avila mount with the young poet Andrés Bello, the former tutor of Simón Bolívar, who later became the leader of independence in northern South America.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt met the Venezuelan Bolívar himself in 1804 in Paris and spent time with him in Rome.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The documentary record does not support the supposition that Humboldt inspired Bolívar to participate in the struggle for independence, but it does indicate Bolívar's admiration for Humboldt's production of new knowledge on Spanish America.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In February 1800, Humboldt and Bonpland left the coast with the purpose of exploring the course of the Orinoco River and its tributaries.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This trip, which lasted four months and covered 1,725 miles (2,776 km) of wild and largely uninhabited country, had an aim of establishing the existence of the Casiquiare canal (a communication between the water systems of the rivers Orinoco and Amazon).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Around 19 March 1800, Humboldt and Bonpland discovered dangerous electric eels, whose shock could kill a man.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] To catch them, locals suggested they drive wild horses into the river, which brought the eels out from the river mud, and resulted in a violent confrontation of eels and horses, some of which died.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt and Bonpland captured and dissected some eels, which retained their ability to shock; both received potentially dangerous electric shocks during their investigations.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The encounter made Humboldt think more deeply about electricity and magnetism, typical of his ability to extrapolate from an observation to more general principles.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt returned to the incident in several of his later writings, including his travelogue *Personal Narrative* (1814–29), *Views of Nature* (1807), and *Aspects of Nature* (1849).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Two months later, they explored the territory of the Maipures and that of the then-recently extinct Atures Indians.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt laid to rest the persistent myth of Walter Raleigh's Lake Parime by proposing that the seasonal flooding of the Rupununi savannah had been misidentified as a lake.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] On 24 November 1800, the two friends set sail for Cuba, landing on 19 December, where they met fellow botanist and plant collector John Fraser.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Fraser and his son had been shipwrecked off the Cuban coast, and did not have a license to be in the Spanish Indies.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt, who was already in Cuba, interceded with crown officials in Havana, as well as giving them money and clothing.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Fraser obtained permission to remain in Cuba and explore.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt entrusted Fraser with taking two cases of Humboldt and Bonpland's botanical specimens to England when he returned, for eventual conveyance to the German botanist Willdenow in Berlin.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt and Bonpland stayed in Cuba until 5 March 1801, when they left for the mainland of northern South America again, arriving there on 30 March.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt is considered to be the "second discoverer of Cuba" due to the scientific and social research he conducted on this Spanish colony.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] During an initial three-month stay at Havana, his first tasks were to survey that city properly and the nearby towns of Guanabacoa, Regla, and Bejucal.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He befriended Cuban landowner and thinker Francisco de Arango y Parreño; together they visited the *Guines* area in south Havana, the valleys of Matanzas Province, and the Valley of the Sugar Mills in Trinidad.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Those three areas were, at the time, the first frontier of sugar production in the island.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] During those trips, Humboldt collected statistical information on Cuba's population, production, technology and trade, and with Arango, made suggestions for enhancing them.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He predicted that the agricultural and commercial potential of Cuba was huge and could be vastly improved with proper leadership in the future.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] On their way back to Europe from the Americas, Humboldt and Bonpland stopped again in Cuba, leaving from the port of Veracruz and arriving in Cuba on 7 January 1804, staying until 29 April 1804.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In Cuba, he collected plant material and made extensive notes.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] During this time, he socialized with his scientific and landowner friends, conducted mineralogical surveys, and finished his vast collection of the island's flora and fauna that he eventually published as *Essai politique sur l'îsle de Cuba*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] After their first stay in Cuba of three months, they returned to the mainland at Cartagena de Indias (now in Colombia), a major center of trade in northern South America.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Ascending the swollen stream of the Magdalena River to Honda, they arrived in Bogotá on 6 July 1801, where they met the Spanish botanist José Celestino Mutis, head of the Royal Botanical Expedition to New Granada, staying there until 8 September 1801.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Mutis was generous with his time and gave Humboldt access to the huge pictorial record he had compiled since 1783.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Mutis was based in Bogotá, but as with other Spanish expeditions, he had access to local knowledge and a workshop of artists, who created highly accurate and detailed images.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This type of careful recording meant that even if specimens were not available to study at a distance, "because the images travelled, the botanists did not have to".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt was astounded at Mutis's accomplishment; when Humboldt published his first volume on botany, he dedicated it to Mutis "as a simple mark of our admiration and acknowledgement".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt had hopes of connecting with the French sailing expedition of Baudin, now finally underway, so Bonpland and Humboldt hurried to Ecuador.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] They crossed the frozen ridges of the Cordillera Real and reached Quito on 6 January 1802, after a tedious and difficult journey.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This was a world record at the time, higher even than had been ascended in a balloon, (for a westerner—Incas had climbed much higher altitudes centuries before), but 1000 feet short of the summit.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt's journey concluded with an expedition to the sources of the Amazon *en route* for Lima, Peru.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] At Callao, the main port for Peru, Humboldt observed the transit of Mercury on 9 November and studied the fertilizing properties of guano, rich in nitrogen, the subsequent introduction of which into Europe was due mainly to his writings.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt and Bonpland had not intended to go to New Spain, but when they were unable to join a voyage to the Pacific, they left the Ecuadorian port of Guayaquil and headed for Acapulco on Mexico's west coast.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Even before Humboldt and Bonpland started on their way to New Spain's capital on Mexico's central plateau, Humboldt realized the captain of the vessel that brought them to Acapulco had reckoned its location incorrectly.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Since Acapulco was the main west-coast port and the terminus of the Asian trade from the Spanish Philippines, having accurate maps of its location was extremely important.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt set up his instruments, surveying the deep-water bay of Acapulco, to determine its longitude.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt and Bonpland landed in Acapulco on 15 February 1803, and from there they went to Taxco, a silver-mining town in modern Guerrero.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In April 1803, he visited Cuernavaca, Morelos.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Impressed by its climate, he nicknamed the city the *City of Eternal Spring*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt and Bonpland arrived in Mexico City, having been officially welcomed via a letter from the king's representative in New Spain, Viceroy Don José de Iturrigaray.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt was also given a special passport to travel throughout New Spain and letters of introduction to intendants, the highest officials in New Spain's administrative districts (intendancies).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This official aid to Humboldt allowed him to have access to crown records, mines, landed estates, canals, and Mexican antiquities from the prehispanic era.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt read the writings of Bishop-elect of the important diocese of Michoacan Manuel Abad y Queipo, a classical liberal, that were directed to the crown for the improvement of New Spain.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] They spent the year in the viceroyalty, traveling to different Mexican cities in the central plateau and the northern mining region.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The first journey was from Acapulco to Mexico City, through what is now the Mexican state of Guerrero.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The route was suitable only for mule train, and all along the way, Humboldt took measurements of elevation.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] When he left Mexico a year later in 1804, from the east coast port of Veracruz, he took a similar set of measures, which resulted in a chart in the *Political Essay*, the physical plan of Mexico with the dangers of the road from Acapulco to Mexico City, and from Mexico City to Veracruz.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This visual depiction of elevation was part of Humboldt's general insistence that the data he collected be presented in a way more easily understood than statistical charts.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] A great deal of his success in gaining a more general readership for his works was his understanding that "anything that has to do with extent or quantity can be represented geometrically.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Statistical projections [charts and graphs], which speak to the senses without tiring the intellect have the advantage of bringing attention to a large number of important facts".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt was impressed with Mexico City, which at the time was the largest city in the Americas, and one that could be counted as modern.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He declared "no city of the new continent, without even excepting those of the United States, can display such great and solid scientific establishments as the capital of Mexico".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He pointed to the Royal College of Mines, the Royal Botanical Garden and the Royal Academy of San Carlos as exemplars of a metropolitan capital in touch with the latest developments on the continent and insisting on its modernity.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He also recognized important criollo savants in Mexico, including José Antonio de Alzate y Ramírez, who died in 1799, just before Humboldt's visit; Miguel Velásquez de León; and Antonio de León y Gama.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt spent time at the Valenciana silver mine in Guanajuato, central New Spain, at the time the most important in the Spanish empire.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The bicentennial of his visit in Guanajuato was celebrated with a conference at the University of Guanajuato, with Mexican academics highlighting various aspects of his impact on the city.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt could have simply examined the geology of the fabulously rich mine, but he took the opportunity to study the entire mining complex as well as analyze mining statistics of its output.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His report on silver mining is a major contribution, and considered the strongest and best informed section of his *Political Essay*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Although Humboldt was himself a trained geologist and mining inspector, he drew on mining experts in Mexico.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] One was Fausto Elhuyar, then head of the General Mining Court in Mexico City, who, like Humboldt was trained in Freiberg.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Another was Andrés Manuel del Río, director of Royal College of Mines, whom Humboldt knew when they were both students in Freiberg.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The Bourbon monarchs had established the mining court and the college to elevate mining as a profession, since revenues from silver constituted the crown's largest source of income.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt also consulted other German mining experts, who were already in Mexico.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] While Humboldt was a welcome foreign scientist and mining expert, the Spanish crown had established fertile ground for Humboldt's investigations into mining.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] For Humboldt, a key question was the influence of climate on the development of these civilizations.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] When he published his *Vues des cordillères*, he included a color image of the Aztec calendar stone (which had been discovered in 1790 buried in the main plaza of Mexico City), along with select drawings of the Dresden Codex and others he sought out later in European collections.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His aim was to muster evidence that these pictorial and sculptural images could allow the reconstruction of prehispanic history.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He sought out Mexican experts in the interpretation of sources from there, especially Antonio Pichardo, who was the literary executor of Antonio de León y Gama's work.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] For American-born Spaniards (criollos) who were seeking sources of pride in Mexico's ancient past, Humboldt's recognition of these ancient works and dissemination in his publications was a boon.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He read the work of exiled Jesuit Francisco Javier Clavijero, which celebrated Mexico's prehispanic civilization, and which Humboldt invoked to counter the pejorative assertions about the new world by Buffon, de Pauw, and Raynal.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt ultimately viewed both the prehispanic realms of Mexico and Peru as despotic and barbaric.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] However, he also drew attention to indigenous monuments and artifacts as cultural productions that had "both ... historical *and* artistic significance".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] One of his most widely read publications resulting from his travels and investigations in Spanish America was the *Essai politique sur le royaum de la Nouvelle Espagne*, quickly translated to English as *Political Essay on the Kingdom of New Spain* (1811).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This treatise was the result of Humboldt's own investigations as well as the generosity of Spanish colonial officials for statistical data.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Leaving from Cuba, Humboldt decided to take an unplanned short visit to the United States.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Knowing that the current U.S. president, Thomas Jefferson, was himself a scientist, Humboldt wrote to him saying that he would be in the United States.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Jefferson warmly replied, inviting him to visit the White House in the nation's new capital.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In his letter Humboldt had gained Jefferson's interest by mentioning that he had discovered mammoth teeth near the Equator.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Jefferson had previously written that he believed mammoths had never lived so far south.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt had also hinted at his knowledge of New Spain.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt's treatise on cinchona was published in English in 1821.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] After arriving in Washington D.C, Humboldt held numerous intense discussions with Jefferson on both scientific matters and also his year-long stay in New Spain.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Jefferson had only recently concluded the Louisiana Purchase, which now placed New Spain on the southwest border of the United States.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The Spanish minister in Washington, D.C. had declined to furnish the U.S. government with information about Spanish territories, and access to the territories was strictly controlled.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt was able to supply Jefferson with the latest information on the population, trade agriculture and military of New Spain.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This information would later be the basis for his *Essay on the Political Kingdom of New Spain* (1810).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Jefferson was unsure of where the border of the newly-purchased Louisiana was precisely, and Humboldt wrote him a two-page report on the matter.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Jefferson would later refer to Humboldt as "the most scientific man of the age".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Albert Gallatin, Secretary of the Treasury, said of Humboldt "I was delighted and swallowed more information of various kinds in less than two hours than I had for two years past in all I had read or heard." Gallatin, in turn, supplied Humboldt with information he sought on the United States.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] After six weeks, Humboldt set sail for Europe from the mouth of the Delaware and landed at Bordeaux on 3 August 1804.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt kept a detailed diary of his sojourn to Spanish America, running some 4,000 pages, which he drew on directly for his multiple publications following the expedition.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The leather-bound diaries themselves are now in Germany, having been returned from Russia to East Germany, where they were taken by the Red Army after World War II.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Following German reunification, the diaries were returned to a descendant of Humboldt.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] For a time, there was concern about their being sold, but that was averted.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] A government-funded project to digitize the Spanish American expedition as well as his later Russian expedition has been undertaken (2014–2017) by the University of Potsdam and the German State Library–Prussian Cultural Heritage Foundation.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt's decades' long endeavor to publish the results of this expedition not only resulted in multiple volumes, but also made his international reputation in scientific circles.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt came to be well-known with the reading public as well, with popular, densely illustrated, condensed versions of his work in multiple languages.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Bonpland, his fellow scientist and collaborator on the expedition, collected botanical specimens and preserved them, but unlike Humboldt who had a passion to publish, Bonpland had to be prodded to do the formal descriptions.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Many scientific travelers and explorers produced huge visual records which remained unseen by the general public until the late nineteenth century.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In the case of the Malaspina Expedition, it was not until the late twentieth century when Mutis's botanical, some 12,000 drawings from New Granada, was published.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt, by contrast, published immediately and continuously, using and ultimately exhausting his personal fortune, to produce both scientific and popular texts.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt's name and fame were made by his travels to Spanish America, particularly his publication of the *Political Essay on the Kingdom of New Spain*; his image as the premier European scientist was a later development.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The achievements of the Bourbon regime, especially in New Spain, were evident in the precise data Humboldt systematized and published.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This memorable expedition may be regarded as having laid the foundation of the sciences of physical geography, plant geography, and meteorology.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Key to that was Humboldt's meticulous and systematic measurement of phenomena with the most advanced instruments then available.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He closely observed plant and animal species in situ, not just in isolation, noting all elements in relation to one other.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He collected specimens of plants and animals, dividing the growing collection so that if a portion was lost, other parts might survive.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt saw the need for an approach to science that could account for the harmony of nature among the diversity of the physical world.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] For Humboldt, "the unity of nature" meant that it was the interrelation of all physical sciences—such as the conjoining between biology, meteorology and geology—that determined where specific plants grew.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He found these relationships by unraveling myriad, painstakingly collected data, data extensive enough that it became an enduring foundation upon which others could base their work.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt viewed nature holistically, and tried to explain natural phenomena without the appeal to religious dogma.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He believed in the central importance of observation, and as a consequence had amassed a vast array of the most sophisticated scientific instruments then available.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Each had its own velvet lined box and was the most accurate and portable of its time; nothing quantifiable escaped measurement.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] According to Humboldt, everything should be measured with the finest and most modern instruments and sophisticated techniques available, for that collected data was the basis of all scientific understanding.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This quantitative methodology would become known as Humboldtian science.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt wrote "Nature herself is sublimely eloquent.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The stars as they sparkle in firmament fill us with delight and ecstasy, and yet they all move in orbit marked out with mathematical precision." However, Andreas Daum has recently revisited the concept of Humboldtian Science and set it apart from "Humboldt's science".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His *Essay on the Geography of Plants* (published first in French and then German, both in 1807) was based on the then novel idea of studying the distribution of organic life as affected by varying physical conditions.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This was most famously depicted in his published cross-section of Chimborazo, approximately two feet by three feet (54 cm × 84 cm) color pictorial, he called *Ein Naturgemälde der Anden* and what is also called the Chimborazo Map.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] It was a fold-out at the back of the publication.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt first sketched the map when he was in South America, which included written descriptions on either side of the cross-section of Chimborazo.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] These detailed the information on temperature, altitude, humidity, atmosphere pressure, and the animal and plants (with their scientific names) found at each elevation.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Plants from the same genus appear at different elevations.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The depiction is on an east-west axis going from the Pacific coast lowlands to the Andean range of which Chimborazo was a part, and the eastern Amazonian basin.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt showed the three zones of coast, mountains, and Amazonia, based on his own observations, but he also drew on existing Spanish sources, particularly Pedro Cieza de León, which he explicitly referred to.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The Spanish American scientist Francisco José de Caldas had also measured and observed mountain environments and had earlier come to similar ideas about environmental factors in the distribution of life forms.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt was thus not putting forward something entirely new, but it is argued that his finding is not derivative either.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The Chimborazo map displayed complex information in an accessible fashion.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The map was the basis for comparison with other major peaks.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] By his delineation (in 1817) of isothermal lines, he at once suggested the idea and devised the means of comparing the climatic conditions of various countries.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This was a major contribution to climatology.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His discovery of the decrease in intensity of Earth's magnetic field from the poles to the equator was communicated to the Paris Institute in a memoir read by him on 7 December 1804.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Its importance was attested by the speedy emergence of rival claims.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His services to geology were based on his attentive study of the volcanoes of the Andes and Mexico, which he observed and sketched, climbed, and measured with a variety of instruments.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] By climbing Chimborazo, he established an altitude record which became the basis for measurement of other volcanoes in the Andes and the Himalayas.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] As with other aspects of his investigations, he developed methods to show his synthesized results visually, using the graphic method of geologic-cross sections.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He showed that volcanoes fell naturally into linear groups, presumably corresponding with vast subterranean fissures; and by his demonstration of the igneous origin of rocks previously held to be of aqueous formation, he contributed largely to the elimination of erroneous views, such as Neptunism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt was a significant contributor to cartography, creating maps, particularly of New Spain, that became the template for later mapmakers in Mexico.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His careful recording of latitude and longitude led to accurate maps of Mexico, the port of Acapulco, the port of Veracruz, and the Valley of Mexico, and a map showing trade patterns among continents.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His maps also included schematic information on geography, converting areas of administrative districts (intendancies) using proportional squares.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The U.S. was keen to see his maps and statistics on New Spain, since they had implication for territorial claims following the Louisiana Purchase.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Later in life, Humboldt published three volumes (1836–1839) examining sources that dealt with the early voyages to the Americas, pursuing his interest in nautical astronomy in the fifteenth and sixteenth centuries.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His research yielded the origin of the name "America", put on a map of the Americas by Martin Waldseemüller.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt conducted a census of the indigenous and European inhabitants in New Spain, publishing a schematized drawing of racial types and populations distribution, grouping them by region and social characteristics.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He estimated the population to be six million individuals.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He estimated Indians to be forty percent of New Spain's population, but their distribution being uneven; the most dense were in the center and south of Mexico, the least dense in the north.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He presented these data in chart form, for easier understanding.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He also surveyed the non-Indian population, categorized as Whites (Spaniards), *Negroes*, and castes (*castas*).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt reported that American-born Spaniards were legally racial equals of those born in Spain, but the crown policy since the Bourbons took the Spanish throne privileged those born in Iberia.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt observed that "the most miserable European, without education and without intellectual cultivation, thinks himself superior to whites born in the new continent".
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The truth in this assertion, and the conclusions derived from them, have been often disputed as superficial, or politically motivated, by some authors, considering that between 40% and 60% of high offices in the new world were held by creoles.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The enmity between some creoles and the peninsular-born whites increasingly became an issue in the late period of Spanish rule, with creoles increasingly alienated from the crown.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt's assessment was that royal government abuses and the example of a new model of rule in the United States were eroding the unity of whites in New Spain.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] One scholar says that his writings contain fantastical descriptions of America, while leaving out its inhabitants, stating that Humboldt, coming from the Romantic school of thought, believed '... nature is perfect till man deforms it with care'.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The further assessment is that he largely neglected the human societies amidst nature.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Views of indigenous peoples as 'savage' or 'unimportant' leaves them out of the historical picture.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Other scholars counter that Humboldt dedicated large parts of his work to describing the conditions of slaves, indigenous peoples, mixed-race castas, and society in general.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He often showed his disgust for the slaveryand inhumane conditions in which indigenous peoples and others were treated and he often criticized Spanish colonial policies.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Humboldt was not primarily an artist, but he could draw well, allowing him to record a visual record of particular places and their natural environment.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Many of his drawings became the basis for illustrations of his many scientific and general publications.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Artists whom Humboldt influenced, such as Johann Moritz Rugendas, followed in his path and painted the same places Humboldt had visited and recorded, such as the basalt formations in Mexico, which was an illustration in his *Vues des Cordillères*.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The editing and publication of the encyclopedic mass of scientific, political and archaeological material that had been collected by him during his absence from Europe was now Humboldt's most urgent desire.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] After a short trip to Italy with Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac for the purpose of investigating the law of magnetic declination and a stay of two and a half years in Berlin, in the spring of 1808, he settled in Paris.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] His purpose for being located there was to secure the scientific cooperation required for bringing his great work through the press.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This colossal task, which he at first hoped would occupy but two years, eventually cost him twenty-one, and even then it remained incomplete.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] During his lifetime Humboldt became one of the most famous men in Europe.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Academies, both native and foreign, were eager to elect him to their membership, the first being The American Philosophical Society in Philadelphia, which he visited at the tail end of his travel through the Americas.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He was elected to the Prussian Academy of Sciences in 1805.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He was elected a foreign member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences in 1810.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The Royal Society, whose president Sir Joseph Banks had aided Humboldt as a young man, now welcomed him as a foreign member.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] After Mexican independence from Spain in 1821, the Mexican government recognized him with high honors for his services to the nation.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In 1827, the first President of Mexico, Guadalupe Victoria granted Humboldt Mexican citizenship and in 1859, the President of Mexico, Benito Juárez, named Humboldt a hero of the nation (*benemérito de la nación*).
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The gestures were purely honorary; he never returned to the Americas following his expedition.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Importantly for Humboldt's long-term financial stability, King Frederick William III of Prussia conferred upon him the honor of the post of royal chamberlain, without at the time exacting the duties.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] The appointment had a pension of 2,500 thalers, afterwards doubled.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] This official stipend became his main source of income in later years when he exhausted his fortune on the publications of his research.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] Financial necessity forced his permanent relocation to Berlin in 1827 from Paris.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In Paris he found not only scientific sympathy, but the social stimulus which his vigorous and healthy mind eagerly craved.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] He was equally in his element as the lion of the salons and as the savant of the Institut de France and the observatory.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] On 12 May 1827 he settled permanently in Berlin, where his first efforts were directed towards the furtherance of the science of terrestrial magnetism.
[src:bernard-germain-de-lacépède/alexander-von-humboldt-p02] In 1827, he began giving public lectures in Berlin, which became the basis for his last major publication, *Kosmos* (1845–1862).
